Particle methods in ocean and coastal engineering

Highlights

  • •

    The review is presented in three main categories of wave hydrodynamics, wave-structure interaction and wave-current-sediment interaction.

  • •

  • •

Abstract

This paper aims at providing a state-of-the-art review on the applications of particle methods in hydrodynamics-related problems in ocean and coastal engineering. The problems are placed into three categories according to their physical characteristics, namely, wave hydrodynamics and corresponding mass (air, oil, etc.) transport, wave-structure interaction, and wave-current-sediment interaction. For the first category, particle-based simulations of wave generation, propagation, breaking, as well as the associated turbulence production and dissipation, air entrainment, and mass transport, are reviewed. For wave-structure interaction, extensive structural types are considered that include fixed and moving (floating) structures, rigid and deformable structures, impermeable and porous structures, etc. For the third category, the latest advances of particle methods in wave/current interaction with sediments, i.e., sediment transport and coastal morphological changes, are outlined. This article also reviews the latest developments of particle methods with respect to enhancement of numerical stability, accuracy, efficiency and consistency in order to handle the multi-physics and multi-scale problems emerging from coastal and ocean engineering practices. Finally, the future perspectives of extending particle methods to a wider range of ocean and coastal engineering applications are highlighted.

1. Introduction

The ocean and coastal regions are of significant social and economic value. Human activities have increased in these areas for recreational purposes and the exploitation of ocean resources. Among various factors that affect the safe and sustainable operation of these activities, a reliable hydrodynamic analysis of the ocean environment and its interaction with ocean structures and facilities is crucially important, especially under the background of climate change and the associated increase in global wave power (Reguero et al., 2019). The major hydrodynamic processes concerned in ocean and coastal engineering are illustrated in Fig. 1, which include wave hydrodynamics processes comprising wave propagation, breaking, and the resulting turbulence and aerated flows; wave/current interactions with ocean and coastal structures such as ships, oil/gas platforms, subsea structures and porous breakwater; and wave/current-sediment interaction. A large number of analytical, experimental and numerical studies have been conducted for better understanding of these problems, whereas many of the recent efforts have been focused on numerical modelling due to the rapid development of computational techniques and hardware, as well as detailed information that computational methods can provide.

Despite their advantageous features, numerical methods may face several considerable challenges when applied to ocean and coastal engineering. The main numerical difficulties to model the foregoing ocean and coastal engineering problems include the presence of highly deformed moving interfaces involving complex physics as in the case of wave breaking and associated fluid turbulence, strongly entangled interactions of waves and rigid/deformable moving structures, nonlinear interactions between fluids/solids of different physical properties as in the case of water-air and water-sediment interactions, etc. To address these issues, numerical methods that solve the governing equations on computational meshes, i.e., the so-called mesh-based methods, have been extensively developed and applied. These include the Finite Volume Method (FVM) (Chen et al., 2014, Xie et al., 2020b), Finite Difference Method (FDM) (Lin and Liu, 1998a, Martin et al., 2021), Finite Element Method (FEM) (Wu et al., 1998, Ma and Yan, 2009) and Boundary Element Method (BEM) (Bai and Eatock Taylor, 2007, Ning et al., 2015) that solve either the Navier-Stokes equations for viscous flows or the Laplace equation for potential flows. For instance, Fully Nonlinear Potential Flow (FNPT) have been accurately solved by either FVM (e.g., Lin et al. (2021)), FDM (e.g., Hicks et al. (2021)), FEM (e.g., Ma et al. (2001)) and BEM (e.g., Dombre et al. (2019)) for simulation of nonlinear water wave problems. In parallel, mesh-based viscous flow solvers have been continuously developed and applied in a wide range of ocean and coastal engineering problems. For instance, several robust FVM solvers to Navier-Stokes equations include OpenFOAM (e.g., Di Paolo et al. (2021)), STAR-CCM+ (e.g., Judge et al. (2020)), ANSYS-FLUENT (e.g., Masumi and Nikseresht (2019)). Although having achieved great successes in the last decades, these methods are still facing challenges in some aspects of the abovementioned issues (Vacondio et al., 2021) including problems involving complex topological changes and highly deformed moving interfaces.

Another category of numerical methods, i.e., Lagrangian particle methods, has been attracting many interests in the ocean and coastal engineering community due to their intrinsic advantages in three aspects. First, particle-based discretization, free from meshes, makes particle methods naturally capable of modelling large deformations (e.g., fluid merging and splitting). Second, due to their Lagrangian feature and the absence of the advection terms in the governing equations, particle methods are free from the numerical diffusion corresponding to the discretization of advection terms, and hence are superior in modelling advection-dominated flows (e.g., violent free surface flows). Third, the Lagrangian and particle-based features make particle methods suitable for multi-phase interaction problems (e.g., wave-structure and wave-sediment). The particle methods have been achieving tremendous developments in fundamental theories and numerical technologies in the last two decades, and their applications have been extended from small-scale two-dimensional (2D) single-physics problems to real-scale three-dimensional (3D) multi-physics problems. Indeed, particle methods have become an important computational tool for scientific research and industrial design.

To date, various particle methods have been developed for simulation of incompressible fluid flows and their interactions with surrounding environments. In this regard, particle methods can be classified into the weakly compressible and the incompressible (or projection-based) methods. In weakly compressible methods, the fluid pressure is related to the fluid density explicitly through an equation of state (EOS), which models fluid as weakly compressible. The first and most famous weakly compressible particle method is the Smoothed Particle Hydrodynamics (SPH) that was originally invented for solving astrophysical problems (Gingold and Monaghan, 1977, Lucy, 1977) and firstly extended for fluid dynamics problems by Monaghan (1994). The weakly compressible SPH is also termed as WCSPH. The explicit computation scheme of WCSPH makes it conveniently parallelizable. The early versions of WCSPH suffered from the issue of spurious pressure fluctuations arising from acoustic perturbations and local particle-based numerical approximations (Meringolo et al., 2017). This issue has been extensively addressed by several strategies such as the diffusive term (e.g., Molteni and Colagrossi (2009)), particle shifting (e.g., Lind et al. (2012)), and higher-order particle interpolation schemes (e.g., Khayyer and Gotoh (2012)) (more details will be presented in Section 2.3). Several highly recognized SPH open source codes are based on the WCSPH method. The open source codes that have been used in ocean and coastal hydrodynamics include SPHysics (Gomez-Gesteira et al., 2012), GPUSPH (Hérault et al., 2010), DualSPHysics (Crespo et al., 2015, Domínguez et al., 2021), SPHinXsys (Zhang et al., 2020a) and SPHERA (Amicarelli et al., 2020). Other weakly compressible particle methods include the Finite Particle Method (Liu et al., 2005) and the weakly compressible MPS (Moving Particle Semi-implicit) method (Shakibaeinia and Jin, 2010).

In incompressible particle methods, the fluid incompressibility is imposed strictly by solving a pressure Poisson equation (PPE) derived based on Chorin's projection scheme (Chorin, 1968) on the basis of a rigorous mathematical concept, i.e., Helmholtz-Leary decomposition (Gotoh and Khayyer, 2018). The first particle method adopting this solving strategy is the MPS method that was invented by Koshizuka et al. (1995) and Koshizuka and Oka (1996) for simulation of free surface flows including dambreak induced breaking waves. The semi-implicit scheme of projection-based particle methods alleviates the spurious fluctuations considerably, which is a major advantage as compared to the weakly compressible particle methods. However, the solution process of a linear equation system (of pressure) is time-consuming and is more difficult for parallelization. Cummins and Rudman (1999) implemented a similar idea into the SPH framework and studied the cavity flow problems. Lo and Shao (2002) and Shao and Lo (2003) extended the projection-based SPH to the simulation of free surface flows and named it incompressible SPH (ISPH). Ma (2005a) proposed the Meshless Local Petrov Galerkin (MLPG) method in the projection-based framework and later enhanced it by introducing a Rankine source solution, resulting in the MLPG_R (Ma, 2005b). The key feature of MLPG_R is that the Poisson's equation is transferred into a weak form that does not contain any derivatives of functions. By conducting rigorous analyses, Ma et al. (2016) showed that even using simple approximations, the MLPG_R scheme can achieve the second-order convergent rate in patch tests. Another projection-based particle method is the Consistent Particle Method (CPM) proposed by Koh et al. (2012) that achieves mathematical consistency in computing spatial derivatives. It should be noted that the comparison of weakly compressible and incompressible particle methods is beyond the scope of this study and such studies are referred to Lee et al. (2008), Shadloo et al. (2012), Chen et al. (2013b) and Vittoz et al. (2019).

We have witnessed prosperous developments in particle method theories and technologies. These developments have been elaborated in monographs (Liu and Liu, 2003, Violeau, 2012, Gotoh et al., 2013) and recent review papers with focuses on different aspects (Gotoh and Khayyer, 2016, Shadloo et al., 2016, Violeau and Rogers, 2016, Wang et al., 2016b, Gotoh and Khayyer, 2018, Liu and Zhang, 2019, Ye et al., 2019, Li et al., 2020a, Lind et al., 2020, Vacondio et al., 2021). The present article attempts to provide a review of particle methods from a different perspective, i.e., to present an in-depth, up-to-date and comprehensive review of the latest developments and applications of particle methods in ocean and coastal engineering problems, which are classified into three major categories: (i) wave hydrodynamics and corresponding mass transport (Section 3), (ii) wave/current-structure interactions (Section 4), and (iii) wave/current-sediment interaction and resultant sediment transport/morphological changes (Section 5). The final section of the article is dedicated to concluding remarks and future perspectives corresponding to further enhancement/extension of particle methods. While focusing more on SPH and its variants, this review also considers other important particle methods applied in ocean and coastal engineering including MPS, MLPG_R, MPM (Material Point Method), FVPM (Finite Volume Particle Method), etc.

2. Mathematical formulations and numerical developments

2.1. Governing equations and boundary conditions

The weakly compressible particle methods solve the conservation equations of mass and momentum, i.e., the continuity and Navier-Stokes (NS) equations, in the Lagrangian form. The Einstein notation form of the equations reads(1)1ρDρDt+∂ui∂xi=0(2)DuiDt=−1ρ∂p∂xi+ν∂2ui∂xj∂xj+giwhere ui is the fluid velocity, p the pressure, ρ the density, ν the kinematic viscosity and gi the body force. The continuity and NS equations are often closed by a stiff EOS, the commonly used forms of which read (Antuono et al., 2010, Crespo et al., 2015)(3)p=c02(ρ−ρ0)and(4)p=c02ρ0γ[(ρρ0)γ−1]where c0 is the speed of sound, ρ0 the reference density, and γ a constant number taken to be 7 for water. To capture the near-incompressible flow features, c0 ≥ 10umax is normally adopted, where umax is the maximum particle velocity during the simulation. In this category, the WCSPH is prevailing, and the corresponding coherently developed models include the standard WCSPH (Dalrymple and Rogers, 2006) and its variants such as the δ-SPH with diffusive terms (Molteni and Colagrossi, 2009), as well as the Riemann SPH enhanced by the Riemann solver (Monaghan, 1997, Omidvar et al., 2012, Zhang et al., 2017b). The WCMPS has achieved successes in hydraulic engineering problems; however, its applications in ocean and coastal engineering are limited.

The projection-based particle methods solve the continuity and NS equations for incompressible fluids. In this case, the continuity equation becomes(5)∂ui∂xi=0

The governing equations are often solved by a standard two-step prediction-correction projection scheme that enforces the incompressibility condition strictly. The projection scheme results in a PPE that can be considered in either one of the following forms (Koshizuka et al., 1998, Lo and Shao, 2002, Hu and Adams, 2007, Xu et al., 2009):(6)∂2p(n+1)∂xi2=−1Δt(DρDt)*(7)∂2p(n+1)∂xi2=ρΔt∂ui*∂xiwhere (n+1) implies the (n+1)th time step and the superscript * corresponds to the intermediate stage in the two-step projection scheme. Note that Eqs. (6) and (7) are equivalent in the continuous form and may differ in the discretized form. The major projection-based particle methods include the MPS (Koshizuka and Oka, 1996), ISPH (Lo and Shao, 2002), MLPG_R (Ma and Zhou, 2009), and CPM (Koh et al., 2012).

The governing equations in weakly compressible and incompressible methods are discretized/solved through particle-based differential operators in a Lagrangian meshfree manner. Despite the advantages of flexibility and potential robustness in simulating advection-dominated fluid flows, especially those characterized by highly deformed moving boundaries, the purely Lagrangian meshfree solution may face several challenges. These challenges, corresponding to stability, convergence, adaptivity, boundary conditions, etc., are considered as so-called SPH grand challenges initiated by SPHERIC (Vacondio et al., 2021), and are effectively addressed and comprehensively summarized in recent research contributions (Gotoh and Khayyer, 2018, Lind et al., 2020, Vacondio et al., 2021). The present article summarizes several aspects of the numerical developments corresponding to the imposition of boundary conditions, stability/accuracy, and computational efficiency in Sections 2.2 through 2.4.

2.2. Boundary conditions in particle methods

As for the boundary conditions, the fluid motion at surface or interface follows two types of boundary conditions, namely, the kinematic one corresponding to zero mass flux on a macroscopic scale across the interface and the dynamic one corresponding to stress continuity at the interface. As for the free surface, the well-known Kinematic Free Surface Boundary Condition (KFSBC) and the Dynamic Free Surface Boundary Condition (DFSBC) imply the continuity of fluid motion and stress at the free surface. The kinematic and dynamic boundary conditions are also applicable to the fluid flows passing through porous media that will be discussed in Section 4.4.

On an impermeable solid wall that can be either fixed, moving-rigid, or deformable, fluids cannot penetrate the wall surface. For viscous flows, the adjacent fluid particles also adhere to the wall (no relative motion). Hence, the non-slip boundary condition for velocity and the Neumann boundary condition for pressure apply. In simulations, the numerical resolution may not be adequate to capture the boundary layer effect in the vicinity of the solid boundary and hence the free-slip boundary condition is sometimes adopted. The general form of the Neumann pressure boundary reads ∂p/∂n = ρ[−DubDt·n−(ub−u)·(ωb×u)+g·n], where ub and ωb represent the velocity and angular velocity of a solid boundary, respectively, u indicates the fluid velocity, g denotes the body force field induced by gravity, and n signifies the outward unit vector of the wall (Antuono et al., 2011). In non-slip simulations, the term relating to ωb disappears. In the modelling of wave/current inflowing/outflowing a domain, the continuity of fluid properties at the inflow/outflow boundaries should be satisfied.

2.2.1. Free surface boundary

The KFSBC would be automatically satisfied in single-phase particle-based simulations, thanks to the Lagrangian meshfree treatment. As shown by Colagrossi et al. (2009) and Colagrossi et al. (2011), the DFSBC would also be satisfied in WCSPH in integral form. After discretization, due to possible numerical errors and perturbations in particle motion at the free surface, the continuity of stress through a continuous material surface (as free surface) may not be guaranteed. This is also the case for projection particle methods even though in these methods the DFSBC is explicitly applied during the solution of PPE by giving zero pressure to free surface particles.

The DFSBC can be further improved by enhancing the accuracy of the solutions to velocity and pressure fields through the application of consistent and conservative schemes. Indeed, minimization of perturbations in particle motion, as well as noise in the pressure field, would ensure a continuous material surface with constant stress (zero-gauge pressure) as the free surface boundary. A recent study (Wang et al., 2019a) showed that through the application of a so-called BM (Background Mesh) scheme, continuity of source term of PPE and thus pressure field could be enhanced at free surfaces, resulting in more continuous free surfaces with better satisfaction of DFSBC. In the context of WCSPH, You et al. (2021) have shown the advantage of incorporation of BM scheme to enhance the accuracy of density/pressure field through achieving a spatially more continuous/accurate instantaneous time variation of density. The BM scheme in WCSPH framework has been proven effective in enhancing the physical resolution of continuity equation at free surfaces and in particular improving the satisfaction of DFSBC through providing a more accurate resolution of material discontinuities.

In incompressible particle methods where the zero pressure needs to be applied at the free surface (as a Dirichlet boundary condition) and in some incompressible/weakly-compressible particle methods where numerical treatments for particles near the free surface (e.g., the particle shifting scheme in Sun et al. (2017a) and Khayyer et al. (2017a)) are needed, the recognition of the free surface particles is essential. This can be achieved by three approaches, namely, i) calculation of a kernel-based interpolated indicator at a target particle based on the distribution of neighbor particles, ii) geometrical indicator based on the geometrical profile of particles, iii) hybrid approach combining approaches i and ii. Regarding the first approach, several implementations include evaluating the particle (number) density (Koshizuka et al., 1998, Shao and Lo, 2003), divergence of particle position (Lee et al., 2008, Khayyer et al., 2017a), summation of x or y coordinates of neighbor particles (Khayyer et al., 2009), eigenvalue of a renormalization matrix (Marrone et al., 2010) or color function (Zheng et al., 2021). The first category of approaches is efficient but may lead to misjudgment of inner fluid particles as free-surface, especially in case of the presence of irregularity in particle distributions. As for the second category of approaches that judges the free surface particles by analyzing the geometrical relationship of particles (Dilts, 2000, Koh et al., 2012, Luo et al., 2016a, Suchde, 2021), generally, the implemented schemes are accurate, however, computationally less efficient. To incorporate the advantages of both categories of approaches, hybrid approaches, the third category of approaches, have been proposed (Marrone et al., 2010, Zheng et al., 2012, Liu et al., 2014, Sun et al., 2017a), in which a common strategy is to use the foregoing first category of approach for preliminary detection of particles near the free surface and then adopt the geometrical approach for a refined judgment.

2.2.2. Solid boundary

To model the impermeability and non-slip/free-slip conditions on impermeable boundaries, several solid boundary approaches have been developed. These approaches include the repulsive force approach used in WCSPH (Monaghan, 1994, Monaghan and Kajtar, 2009, Monaghan and Mériaux, 2018), the dummy particle approach (deploying particles outside the solid boundary that are either fixed or moving in accordance with the boundary) extensively applied in incompressible particle methods (Koshizuka et al., 1998, Shao and Lo, 2003), the Dynamic Boundary Condition (DBC) (Crespo et al., 2007) extensively utilized in WCSPH (Gomez-Gesteira et al., 2012, Crespo et al., 2015, Verbrugghe et al., 2019), and the ghost particle approach (mirroring particles of fluid particles through the tangential line of a solid boundary) (Lo and Shao, 2002, Colagrossi and Landrini, 2003) successfully adopted in both incompressible and weakly-compressible particle methods. Each boundary approach has its merits and limitations in terms of accuracy, implementation, and capability in handling complex boundaries.

The fixed ghost particle (Antuono et al., 2011, Marrone et al., 2011) has been receiving increasing interest, due to its feature in inheriting the accuracy of the mirror particle approach and the efficiency of handling complex boundaries of the fixed particle approach. This approach was extended by recognizing the active ghost particle whose interpolation node was immersed in fluids (to enhance the computational accuracy near the intersections of fluid surfaces and solid boundaries) (Bouscasse et al., 2013b) and by linking a single boundary particle to several interpolation particles to treat thin solid boundaries (Meringolo et al., 2015). This approach has been adopted in δ-SPH models and many other recent WCSPH simulations. Recently, English et al. (2021) presented a modified Dynamic Boundary Conditions (mDBC) through consideration of fixed boundary particles with first-order consistent SPH interpolations incorporated for evaluation of density of boundary particles using the density of corresponding ghost node (mirrored boundary particle) and its gradient. Clear improvements were achieved through application of mDBC with respect to DBC, in terms of both pressure calculation at the wall boundary as well as particle distribution in the vicinity of the wall boundary.

Another approach is the semi-analytical wall boundary originally proposed based on WCSPH (Ferrand et al., 2013), which avoids deploying fictitious particles and models the effects of solid boundaries by boundary integral terms and a renormalizing factor. This boundary scheme was implemented into ISPH (Leroy et al., 2014) and extended to unsteady open boundaries (Ferrand et al., 2017). Chiron et al. (2019) introduced a cut-face scheme to the semi-analytical wall boundary to cope with the discretization of solid boundaries that are not constrained by particles, offering more flexibilities in dealing with 3D complex boundaries. The advantage of avoiding fictitious particles beyond solid boundaries was recently incorporated into MPS (Matsunaga et al., 2020). Also noteworthy is that the ISPH model of Zheng et al. (2018a) would also become free from using fictitious particles outside the solid boundary by adopting the Simplified Finite Difference Interpolation in MLPG_R (Ma and Zhou, 2009, Sriram and Ma, 2012) for imposing the pressure boundary on solid surfaces. This is advantageous for modelling solid boundaries of complex shapes.

To enhance the accuracy of SPH close to solid boundaries, Fernandez-Gutierrez et al. (2017) presented a hybrid Lagrangian Voronoi–SPH scheme, where the SPH discretization was substituted by Voronoi elements close to solid boundaries along with incorporation of a so-called buffer zone to couple Voronoi and SPH subdomains. In Nasar et al. (2019), the Eulerian WCSPH model has been coupled with the immersed boundary method for slender solid boundaries.

2.3. Stability and accuracy

The stability of a computational method is among the most crucial aspects to ensure its reliability and applicability. As for particle methods, there are generally two types of instabilities, namely, rank deficiency (Beissel and Belytschko, 1996) and state of stress instability (Bonet and Kulasegaram, 2001). The rank deficiency instability is related to spurious singular or zero-energy modes occurring when the field variables and their derivatives are calculated at the same discretization points. The state of stress instability depends on the state of stress and more specifically on the growth of perturbations linked with kernel-based approximations of inter-particle interactions. With respect to the designed form of kernels in particle methods and corresponding approximations (Swegle et al., 1995), particle methods are mainly prone to so-called tensile instability, where the growth of perturbations are likely to occur in tensile stress states.

To resolve the rank deficiency instability, auxiliary computational points, referred to as, stress points (Dyka et al., 1997, Randles and Libersky, 2000) are introduced in between the particles to contain the mechanical properties, while the particles continue to represent the kinematics. To resolve the tensile instability, efforts have been made to minimize the non-physical perturbations in particle motion through enhancing the accuracy via more consistent/accurate differential operator models (e.g., Dilts (1999)), as well as maintaining the regularity of particle distributions through the incorporation of particle regularization schemes such as the particle shifting (Lind et al., 2012, Khayyer et al., 2017a). In structural mechanics, incorporation of so-called Lagrangian kernels (Belytschko and Xiao, 2002) and total Lagrangian formalism (Vignjevic et al., 2006) have been shown to be effective in treating the tensile instability. Although incorporation of artificial stress or force (Gray et al., 2001, Kondo et al., 2009) may also minimize the tensile instability, it is not preferred due to possible adverse effects such as non-physical energy dissipation.

As for accuracy enhancement, we can categorize the developments into two groups for fully explicit weakly compressible particle methods (e.g., WCSPH) and those for semi-implicit projection particle methods (e.g., ISPH, MPS). Regarding fully-explicit particle methods, notable accuracy enhancing schemes comprise of Corrected SPH (Bonet and Lok, 1999), δ-SPH (Molteni and Colagrossi, 2009), δ+-SPH (Sun et al., 2017a), Riemann schemes (Monaghan, 1997, Omidvar et al., 2013, Oger et al., 2016b) and careful implementation of so-called Background Pressure (e.g., Sun et al. (2021b) and Moghimi and Quinlan (2019)). A key aspect for enhancement of accuracy/stability in particle methods corresponds to avoiding the anisotropic spatial distribution of particles that are prone to be formed due to purely Lagrangian nature of these methods. In this regard, particle shifting technology (Lind et al., 2012, Khayyer et al., 2017a) and transport velocity formulations (Adami et al., 2013, Oger et al., 2016b) have shown to be effective.

Regarding accuracy enhancement in the context of projection particle methods, several developments have been made through improved momentum conservation (Khayyer and Gotoh, 2008, Khayyer et al., 2008), as well as refined differential operators with higher-order accuracy and better consistency (Khayyer and Gotoh, 2010, Khayyer and Gotoh, 2012, Koh et al., 2012, Zheng et al., 2014, Luo et al., 2015, Zheng et al., 2017). Xu and Lin (2017) developed a novel two-step projection ISPH method through the implementation of a careful algorithm and consideration of calculated pressure fields at two consecutive time steps in the projection process. The model was verified in the simulation of linear and solitary wave propagations in constant water depth and nonlinear wave transformation over a submerged breakwater. The new two-step projection ISPH was shown to have enhanced energy conservation properties. The particle shifting technology of Xu et al. (2009) and Lind et al. (2012) has been shown to be a promising scheme to enhance the accuracy of projection particle methods including both ISPH (e.g., Xenakis et al. (2017) and Rezavand et al. (2018)) and MPS (e.g., Duan et al. (2018) and Khayyer et al. (2019a)). Khayyer et al. (2017a) presented a corrected version of particle shifting scheme (Lind et al., 2012) for free-surface flows referred to as OPS (Optimized Particle Shifting) scheme. The OPS scheme is free of tuning parameters and effectively eliminates shifting normal to free-surfaces. Khayyer et al. (2019a) proposed a novel algorithm through incorporation of the OPS scheme for stable and accurate reproduction of multi-phase flows characterized by large-density ratios with discontinuous material interfaces. Thanks to developments made for enhancing the stability and accuracy of both explicit and projection particle methods, these methods have been successfully applied to several important yet numerically challenging problems in coastal and ocean engineering (e.g., SPH for violent waves interacting with Wave Energy Converters by Marrone et al. (2019) or MPS for swash morphodynamics by Harada et al. (2018).

Linked with the accuracy of particle methods, we need to pay close attention to conservation features of these new-generation methods including energy conservation. Violeau (2012) highlighted the compatibility, and more precisely, the skew-adjointness of gradient and divergence operators for energy conservation. In the context of projection-based particle methods, the skew-adjointness of gradient and divergence operators is required for an exact projection (Cummins and Rudman, 1999), which is a necessity for an exact energy conservation. Khayyer et al. (2017b) conducted a detailed study on energy conservation properties of projection-based particle methods, i.e., MPS and ISPH. The significance of Taylor-series consistent pressure gradient models and enhancing effect of the consistency-related Gradient Correction (GC) scheme (Khayyer and Gotoh, 2011, Gotoh et al., 2014) in providing enhanced energy conservation were highlighted.

It is worth noting that recent research efforts have shown the effectiveness of the careful incorporation of Eulerian and/or mesh-based schemes within the context of particle methods for achieving higher-order of accuracy and convergence. Examples of such efforts include the finite volume particle method (Quinlan et al., 2014, Quinlan, 2018) and the Eulerian ISPH (Lind and Stansby, 2016, Fourtakas et al., 2018b, Nasar et al., 2021). In some cases, researchers have tried to keep the method Lagrangian and mesh-free by solely using the BM scheme (Wang et al., 2019a, You et al., 2021), to calculate a more accurate and spatially continuous time variation of density at background nodes and then at the moving calculation points, i.e., particles.

The reliability of particle methods depends on their convergence properties. As it has been elegantly summarized in a recent review paper by Lind et al. (2020), several factors contribute to convergence properties of particle methods, among which are: regularity of particle distributions, higher-order schemes, higher-order kernels, minimized truncation errors, as well as precise incorporation of boundary conditions. With regard to the particle distribution issue, several rigorous studies have been performed, including the studies by Dehnen and Aly (2012), as well as Litvinov et al. (2015). Through consideration of fixed (Eulerian) particle distributions, Lind and Stansby (2016) demonstrated that high order convergence (up to sixth order) can be achieved by their high-order Eulerian ISPH (EISPH). Interestingly, Lind and Stansby (2016) showed that the distinct advantageous (Lagrangian) features of SPH could be preserved through merging from Eulerian to Lagrangian regions in an Arbitrary-Lagrangian-Eulerian (ALE) fashion. Through the application of the PST (Particle Shifting Technology (Xu et al., 2009, Lind et al., 2012)) in the Lagrangian region, Fourtakas et al. (2018b) demonstrated that Eulerian-Lagrangian ISPH (ELI-SPH) could be established with a sharp interface without a transition region. In a thorough mathematical study, Franz and Wendland (2018) provided explicit relations between the smoothing and discretization parameters to ensure the convergence of SPH solutions for Euler equations and for a specific barotropic flow. They proved convergence for a specific barotropic flow problem under appropriate conditions on the underlying kernel. Recently and in continuation of their previous studies, Franz and Wendland (2021) showed that the generalized Wendland kernels satisfy the approximation condition of any order, meaning that for these kernels the dependence of the convergence rate on the approximation condition can be eliminated. Yan et al. (2020) presented a so-called quadric semi-analytical finite-difference interpolation (QSFDI) scheme to achieve efficient and high-order convergence rate in discretisation of Laplacian in Lagrangian meshfree methods.

2.4. Computational efficiency

Particle methods are computationally demanding due to a relatively large number of neighboring particles associated with a target particle. For projection-based methods where the solution of a linear equation system (of pressure) is needed, the number of associated neighbors means a large number of non-zero elements in the matrix. This, combined with the fact that the coefficients in the equation system lack the ‘banded matrix’ property, makes the numerical solution process of the pressure Poisson equation time-consuming. Hence, the enhancement of computational efficiency has been the topic of substantial studies. These works can be classified into two categories, i.e., the reduction of particles by using non-uniform particle resolution and the increase of the computational speed by parallel computing. The two aspects will be briefly discussed below.

2.4.1. Adaptive resolution

The Lagrangian and meshfree features of particle methods bring about more than a few distinctive advantageous features, in comparison to conventional computational tools. However, the same features may also lead to challenges in the development of so-called adaptive particle methods where the computational resolution can be refined at the local regions of interest or different computational resolutions may be required in multi-physics systems involving physics of different scales. The challenges corresponding to adaptive particle methods are mainly related to the development of consistent and conservative schemes, i.e., schemes that would preserve the overall accuracy, reproducibility, as well as conservation and convergence features of the method. To ensure careful and rigorous developments of adaptive particle methods, adaptivity has been considered as one of the Grand Challenges by the SPHERIC.

Adaptive particle methods not only allow refinement of computational resolution at desired local areas but also guarantee the versatility of the method in treating multi-physics and multi-scale problems. In addition, for efficient applications of particle methods to coastal and ocean engineering, adaptivity would be an important feature, especially for practical 3D simulations where considerable number of computational points (particles)/memory would be required. Through application of adaptive particle methods, the simulations can produce the same level of accuracy but in a manageable and efficient manner.

In the context of SPH, the scheme of variable particle mass distribution was developed and successfully implemented by Omidvar et al. for both 2D (Omidvar et al., 2012) and 3D (Omidvar et al., 2013) wave-structure interactions. Vacondio et al. developed the dynamic particle refinement algorithms in 2D (Vacondio et al., 2013) and 3D (Vacondio et al., 2016). Xiong et al. (2013) implemented Adaptive Particle Splitting and merging (APS) technique for the SPH method on GPU. Barcarolo et al. (2014) combined a particle refinement scheme with a new particle derefinement scheme to SPH. To maintain stability, smoothing in transitional regions of different resolutions were adopted. Hu et al. (2017) considered an improved APS technique together with consistent SPH schemes and particle shifting technology to propose a consistent multi-resolution SPH for FSI corresponding to rigid structures. Sun et al. (2017a) proposed an algorithm for regularizing the particles in multi-resolution δ-SPH simulations through proposal of a generalized particle-shifting scheme. Liu et al. (2018) incorporated a dynamic particle splitting method for multi-resolution SPH simulations with special care to minimize numerical errors at the interface of coarse-fine particles. Wang et al. (2019c) proposed a local dynamic refinement strategy for SPH simulations of FSI corresponding to water entry by rigid solids with a focus on accuracy of the method to carefully resolve the fluid-structure interface. In the context of WCSPH, an impressive application of adaptive particle refinement corresponds to the multi-phase hydroelastic FSI simulations by Sun et al. (2019c) where careful implementations demonstrated the versatility of SPH along with preservation of accuracy. In the framework of SPH, Liu et al. (2020a) developed a particle refinement scheme with a hybrid particle interacting technique for enhanced accuracy with the aim of eliminating interpolation error corresponding to direct interaction of coarse and fine particles. Zhang et al. (2021a) proposed an efficient/accurate multi-resolution SPH for hydroelastic FSI. Sun et al. (2021d) proposed a multi-resolution MPS-DEM model with a generic smoothed wall boundary for hydroelastic FSI. Recently and through incorporation of a particle transport velocity correction, McLoone and Quinlan (2020) presented adaptive and multi-resolution implementations for a weakly compressible scheme in FVPM.

In the context of projection-based particle methods, Tsuruta et al. (2016) proposed a multi-resolution scheme for implementation of MPS for multi-scale refinements. Tang et al. (2016) proposed improved multi-resolution scheme through incorporation of an averaged radius of influence. Shibata et al. (2017) developed an overlapping particle technique that could enable connection of high and low particle resolutions in multi-resolution MPS simulations. Khayyer et al. (2019b) proposed the first multi-resolution hydroelastic FSI solver in the context of projection-based particle methods.

2.4.2. Parallel computing

The computational efficiency of particle methods can also be accelerated by advanced parallelization technologies. The OpenMP (Open Multi-Processing) is easy for coding; however, its application results in limited overall speedup because the overhead for data communication from the shared memory to threads increases significantly with the increase of CPU (Central Processing Unit) threads (Luo and Koh, 2017). The MPI (Message Passing Interface) has been implemented in some WCSPH codes by using massive CPU processors and has resulted in satisfactory scalability, e.g., up to 35,000 processors in Oger et al. (2016a), and up to 1024 processors in Yang et al. (2020a) and Cui et al. (2020). However, the computer clusters are expensive to build/maintain and hence are not easily accessible. The hybrid MPI-OpenMP scheme has also been utilized in some studies such as Marrone et al. (2012) and Wen et al. (2016).

In the last decade, we have witnessed prosperous developments of the CUDA (Compute Unified Device Architecture) programming in particle methods, by using the Graphics Processing Unit (GPU) that is much cheaper for massive GPU cores. For WCSPH, Domínguez et al. (2013) presented a DualSPHysics version with multi-GPUs and used it in simulating a realistic violent wave impact on an oil rig by using more than 109 particles. The computational time was around 1.4 s per time step based on 64 Tesla M2090 GPUs. The efficiency and accuracy of this code have been demonstrated in a variety of ocean and coastal engineering problems such as Mokos et al. (2015), Fourtakas and Rogers (2016), Altomare et al. (2017), Crespo et al. (2017), Canelas et al. (2018), Domínguez et al. (2019a) and Brito et al. (2020). Other GPU parallelized WCSPH codes include Ji et al. (2016) for high-fidelity simulation of water entry, Xia and Liang (2016) for shallow water equations, Ji et al. (2019) for multi-resolution simulation and Zhan et al. (2019) for fluid-structure interaction. The FVPM has also been efficiently implemented on GPU (Alimirzazadeh et al., 2018).

For the projection-based particle methods, the parallelization for the linear function solver for PPE is technically more challenging and a constraint of scalability. Hori et al. (2011) pioneered the presentation of GPU-based implementation of projection particle methods through development of a GPU-MPS code using CUDA. Chow et al. (2018) detailed the single-GPU parallelization of ISPH implemented through converting the WCSPH code DualSPHysics. The single-GPU simulations of several-million particle systems achieved 10-18 times and 1.1-4.5 times speedups compared to the single- and 16-threads CPU simulations, respectively. Chen and Wan (2019a) developed a single-GPU accelerated MPS code, which was demonstrated to achieve a speedup of 33.5 times against single-CPU simulations. The first multi-GPU code of projection-based particle methods (MPS here) was reported in Gou et al. (2019). Based on simulation systems of a maximum of 1.2 million particles, six GPUs achieved an efficiency of 73.68% and a speedup of 4.42 times compared to a single GPU. Recently, Buarque Vieira-e-Silva et al. (2021) showed a maximum speedup of 43 for a single-GPU MPS simulation (against a single-CPU) comprising more than 1.5 million particles. Through consideration of an iterative (and matrix-free) ISPH, Muta et al. (2020) showed speedups comparable to GPU-MPS calculations of Buarque Vieira-e-Silva et al. (2021).

3. Wave hydrodynamics and mass transport

3.1. Generation and propagation of ocean waves and currents

Waves and currents are two major driving forces in ocean and coastal environments. The primary task in the oceanic hydrodynamic analysis is to reproduce waves/currents in a relatively small domain (compared to the sea) that can represent the key features of realistic sea states. The success of this relies on the precise generation of waves and/or currents on the inflow boundaries, minimizing unphysical (numerical) wave dissipations after long-distance propagation and removing unwanted wave reflections. The open boundary approach is often adopted in the modelling of oceanic currents (Bouscasse et al., 2017, Sun et al., 2017a). Waves can be generated by the moving wave maker (Altomare et al., 2017), the inflow boundary approach (Lastiwka et al., 2009, Tafuni et al., 2018, Verbrugghe et al., 2019), the wave relaxation zones (Jacobsen et al., 2012, Altomare et al., 2018), the internal source approach (Liu et al., 2015, Wen and Ren, 2018), and the so-called Wavy Interface scheme (Tsuruta et al., 2021). The wave relaxation zones directly impose the analytical wave properties, e.g., orbital velocity field, in a so-called relaxation zone, while the internal source approach incorporates designed source regions in the domain through modifications of either continuity or momentum equation. A typical example of the internal source approach is depicted in Fig. 2. Regarding the Wavy Interface scheme (Tsuruta et al., 2021), the desired wave profile is generated through careful generation/removal of particles at free-surface zone. The advantages and limitations of these approaches are summarized in Table 1. Waves generated by rigid sliding objects (e.g., landslide) have also been simulated by particle methods (Lin et al., 2015, Zhang et al., 2021b).

Table 1. Advantages and limitations of wave generation approaches in particle methods.

Numerical schemes for accuracy enhancement and better energy conservation (as discussed in Section 2.3) are beneficial for reducing the numerical wave dissipation, which is crucially important for long-distance wave propagation. The unwanted wave reflection from the downstream side wall can be dissipated by the so-called passive wave dissipation via placing a wave damping zone (Liu et al., 2016, Altomare et al., 2017, Sun et al., 2019d). In the simulation of wave-structure interaction, the reflected waves from a structure can propagate back to the wave maker and disturb the wave generation. This undesirable effect can be resolved by the active wave absorption, which corrects the wave properties at the wave generation boundary according to the nearby wave height so as to cancel out the reflected waves (Wen et al., 2016, Altomare et al., 2017, Ni et al., 2018).

Most particle-based simulations have considered 2D wave propagation in a flat-bottom domain. The modelling of regular linear and nonlinear wave propagation has been well resolved. To name just a few, based on the δ-SPH, Antuono et al. (2011) simulated the propagation of regular waves ranging from linear to highly nonlinear. Meringolo et al. (2018) examined the energy evolution and decomposition of regular wave trains during the generation, propagation, and interaction with a curtain breakwater. For DualSPHysics, its fundamentals (moving wave maker) and performance in generating first- and second-order monochromatic waves were detailed in Altomare et al. (2017).

For irregular nonlinear waves, the wave propagation over a submerged breakwater (Beji and Battjes, 1993) has been simulated by different wave generation approaches (Liu et al., 2015, Xu and Lin, 2017, Ni et al., 2018). Fig. 2 depicts the results generated by the internal wave maker of Liu et al. (2015), in which a momentum source term was derived and incorporated to generate the desired wave. In the source region, fluid particles are subjected to additional forces, corresponding to the derived momentum source term, resulting in variation of water surface level and generation of target waves. The generated waves propagated and evolved into nonlinear waves upon passing through the breakwater. The wave elevations above the breakwater were accurately predicted through the ISPH simulation that incorporated an internal wave maker. The irregular random waves have also been successfully simulated, based on the concept of wave superposition (Altomare et al., 2017, Wen and Ren, 2018). As a special case of the irregular nonlinear wave, the freak wave has been reproduced by WCSPH (Antuono et al., 2011, Sun et al., 2019d) and ISPH (Chow et al., 2019). These studies highlighted the necessity of using adequately fine computational resolutions to reproduce large-amplitude waves. Recently, Tsuruta et al. (2021) showed the applicability of their proposed Wavy Interface model to generate desired waves including irregular ones.

The solitary wave has been a popular topic due to its relevance to coastal protection. Substantial studies that have been carried out on solitary wave breaking and interaction with structures. Since the wave-structure interaction will be discussed in later parts, here we only discuss the particle-based studies on the theories of solitary wave generation and propagation. Farhadi et al. (2016) compared the performances of six solitary wave solutions in wave generation based on an ISPH model. Domínguez et al. (2019a) implemented three theories for generating multiple solitary waves in DualSPHysics and compared the wave propagation properties. Francis et al. (2020) conducted SPH simulations and experimental tests, based on which the performance of four solitary wave solutions and two methodologies of solitary wave generation were commented. He et al. (2021) have developed theoretical formulae for solitary wave generation by wedge-, box- and cylinder-shaped plungers, as well as tested their accuracy in 2D SPH simulations.

Coastal regions are often subjected to both waves and current. In analyzing the hydrodynamic problems in such areas, simultaneous modelling of waves and current is needed. Shi et al. (2018a) and He et al. (2018) presented numerical wave-current flumes, in which waves were generated by a moving wave maker and currents were produced by setting inlet/outlet at the upstream/downstream bottom of the flume. By using the inflow boundary approach, Ni et al. (2020a) achieved the simultaneous generation of waves and currents. The influences of the relative direction between wave and current on nonlinear wave propagation and wave breaking over an underwater obstacle were investigated.

Increasing interests are reported in coupling particle methods (modelling highly deformed breaking waves) and other models such as the potential flow model (computationally efficient). In this regard, Sriram et al. (2014) proposed a coupling of the MLPG_R and a FEM-based FNPT model, and studied the 2D non-breaking and breaking waves in a flat-bottom wave flume. Altomare et al. (2015b) developed a one-way coupled DualSPHysics-SWASH model (DualSPHysics used the moving wave maker) and simulated the case of regular waves propagating onshore. This coupled model was extended by replacing the moving wave maker with the relaxation-zone wave generation, which was then used for the irregular wave propagating onshore (Altomare et al., 2018). Followed, Verbrugghe et al. (2018) developed a two-way coupling scheme for hybridizing DualSPHysics and OceanWave3D, which was validated by the propagation of linear and nonlinear waves. Fourtakas et al. (2018a) presented a two-way coupling for ISPH and a FNPT solver (Ma and Yan, 2006) and tested its performance in simulating regular waves. Ni et al. (2020b) developed a coupled SPH-SWE (shallow-water-equation) model and studied the propagation of solitary and standing waves.

The above studies have all been conducted in two-dimensions. Some 3D particle-based simulations of wave propagation have also been reported. Wen et al. (2016) developed a 3D wave basin equipped with OpenMP and MPI technologies based on SPHysics and simulated unidirectional 3D waves. Wei and his co-authors generated 3D short-crested waves by superimposing intersecting wave trains of the same period and different directional angles (Wei and Dalrymple, 2017b, Wei and Dalrymple, 2017a, Wei et al., 2017). In general, the potential of particle methods in precise modelling of the generation, propagation, and transformation of 3D waves needs to be further explored.

3.2. Wave breaking

Wave breaking happens when the amplitude of a wave increases beyond a certain threshold. This can be caused by the wave growing by continuous wind, the propagation of waves to shallow water (i.e., shoaling), and the superimposition of different wave components. The wave breaking is an important factor responsible for wave energy dissipation and mass/energy exchange between sea and air, and hence has been attracting substantial research efforts. Particle methods, due to their meshless nature, possess distinct advantages in modelling the highly deformed breaking waves, which has been well demonstrated in the early works such as, to name just a few, Monaghan (1994), Lo and Shao (2002), Gotoh and Sakai (2006) and Dalrymple and Rogers (2006).

The latest developments of the particle method algorithms (e.g., the diffusive terms, particle shifting, schemes for higher-order accuracy and better energy conservation, etc.) and parallel computing have enabled the high-resolution simulation of breaking waves. By using the WCSPH opensource code SPHysics, Makris et al. (2016) simulated the 2D weakly plunging breakers over a relatively mild slope by examining the wave height, set-up, velocity, and wave-induced mean flow characteristics. The recurring vorticity patterns were derived and the coherent 2D structures inside the surf zone were identified. The authors pointed out the discrepancies at the incipient breaking region and suggested finer-resolution simulations to address the issue. Based on DualSPHysics, Roselli et al. (2019) investigated the 2D periodic wave breaking over a large number of (128) consecutive events on a sloping beach. Instantaneous and phase-averaged wave profiles, fluid velocities, and wave run-up were studied. The SPH prediction up to the onset of wave breaking was in satisfactory agreement with the experimental results, while some discrepancies existed for the wave breaking and post-breaking stages. The authors attributed the discrepancies to the single-phase and 2D simulation. Lowe et al. (2019) simulated the wave breaking over a plane beach and a fringing reef. The wave-induced mass transport and turbulence in the surf zone and the undertow were analyzed.

Based on GPUSPH, Farahani and Dalrymple (2014) studied the 3D turbulent vortical structures under spilling-type broken solitary waves. The simulation detected the reversed horseshoe (hairpin) vortices that were related to sweep turbulent events and played a significant role in transporting momentum and turbulence kinetic energy (TKE). Zainali and Weiss (2015) studied the solitary wave propagation and breaking on the shoreline, as well as the resulting actions on coastal boulders. Wei et al. (2016a) simulated the nearshore tsunami processes. By comparing the experimental results of wave elevation and velocity, the capability of GPUSPH to resolve the wave plunging and collapsing was highlighted. Wei et al. (2017) studied the wave breaking of short-crested waves in the surf zone, as well as the resulting complex flow field such as the rip current and the undertow. The study suggested that the breaking of short-crested waves generates vertical vorticities. Wei and Dalrymple (2018) studied the surf zone wave heating due to the dissipation of breaking wave energy. It has been found that breaking waves in the surf zone increase the internal energy of the water body; the wave-driven currents transport the generated internal energy in the surf zone seaward; the temperature change in the surf zone induced by breaking waves is small (in the order of 0.001 Kelvin). Wei et al. (2018) studied the chaotic behavior of breaking waves. Both laboratory experiments and 3D SPH simulation showed that wave generations with different initial velocity perturbations produce highly repeatable velocity field and free surface profile before wave breaking, but induce considerable variations for the wave splash, plunging jet penetration depth, wave breaking induced turbulence and vortex at the breaking/post-breaking stages.

The solitary wave breaking has also been simulated by particle methods other than GPUSPH. In the category of incompressible particle methods, the CPM that retains good consistency in computing spatial derivatives was adopted to study the solitary wave impact on a seawall (Luo et al., 2019). The wave impinging and overtopping processes and the resulting wave impact pressures/forces were accurately reproduced; the effect of the seawall cross-sectional geometry on the wave overtopping was examined. Using CPM, Ren et al. (2019) simulated the solitary wave breaking upon passing over a submerged breakwater and studied the accompanied vortex generation and evolution. Wang and Liu (2020) presented ISPH simulations of two solitary wave breaking scenarios (i.e., over a submerged breakwater and on a sloping beach) with the focus on the accompanying turbulent features. By using the Finite Point Method, He et al. (2020) simulated the solitary wave breaking over a slope. The pressure field, breaking depth and wave run-up in surging-, plunging- and spilling-breaker scenarios were investigated.

To sum up, the latest particle method technologies give satisfactory modelling of breaking waves up to the initial breaking stage. At the breaking and in particular post-breaking stages when the chaotic nature becomes prominent, simulation results show discrepancies with laboratory measurements. Simulations can be enhanced by employing reliable turbulence models with highly accurate differential operator models to capture the generation, transportation, and dissipation of fluid turbulence, as well as including the air phase in a mathematically-physically-numerically accordant manner to model the multiphase physics. Besides, new experimental data with refined measurements of the kinematic and dynamic properties of the wave breaking process would be valuable.

3.3. Turbulence

Associated with wave breaking is the fluid turbulence that plays a significant role in wave energy transformation and dissipation (Lin and Liu, 1998b). The particle-based turbulence modelling has been the subject of substantial studies and in this regard, a comprehensive review was conducted by Violeau and Issa (2007) that focused on open channel flows. For coastal and oceanic wave hydrodynamics, the fluid turbulence is taken into account predominantly by two strategies, although some others have been developed such as the SPH-ε model (Monaghan, 2011, Monaghan, 2017). These two strategies are the k-ε model that models the Reynolds stress in the RANS (Reynold-Averaged Naiver-Stokes) equations and the sub-particle scale (SPS) model that captures the effects of unresolved small-scale fluid motions in the Large-Eddy Simulation (LES) framework.

3.3.1. RANS model

Applying the Reynolds decomposition to the NS equations results in the RANS equations, which contain the time-averaged mean (over a time period) components and the instantaneous fluctuating components. In a RANS simulation, the mean flow variables are solved, while the fluctuating components are modelled by a proper closure model to reflect the turbulence characteristics and their influences on the mean flow. The k-ε model is one of the most frequently used closure models and details of this model are referred to Lin and Liu (1998a).

The pioneering work implementing the k-ε model into a particle method was based on the ISPH method of Shao (2006b). The author studied periodic spilling and plunging breakers. The performance of the model in predicting the mean flow velocity and turbulence intensity was validated against experimental data. Later, Shao (2006a) used the model for the wave breaking on and overtopping a sloping sea wall. For WCSPH, Issa et al. (2010) conducted RANS simulations of solitary wave breaking on a sloping beach by employing several models describing k and/or ε. The simulation results of wave profiles were compared with benchmark data and the TKE was discussed qualitatively, indicating the importance of including the turbulence effects in simulation. The authors pointed out that the simulations suffered from pressure noises, which in our opinion deteriorated the real fluctuations associated with fluid turbulence.

Recently, Wang and Liu (2020) presented an ISPH model with the k-ε closure and demonstrated its performance in capturing the turbulent features of single solitary waves. Two experimental cases were studied, i.e., solitary wave propagating over a bottom-mounted barrier (Wu et al., 2012) and solitary wave spilling breaking on a sloping beach (Ting, 2006). In the former case, the overall turbulence structures and their evolutions were reproduced satisfactorily with the maximum TKE near the eye of the vortex being underestimated. In the latter case, a comprehensive set of quantities was studied, including the TKE and the turbulent shear stress. The ISPH model satisfactorily captured the magnitude of the TKE after wave breaking, the timing of the peak kinetic energy and turbulence shear stress, and the decay of these quantities. These data provided important benchmarks for follow-up studies.

In the k-ε turbulence modelling, the initial and inflow boundary conditions for k and ε are important numerical parameters. The implementation of these in particle-based simulations was established in Shao (2006b). These have been adopted by most of the subsequent particle-based k-ε turbulence modelling. Some works investigated the influence of the initial turbulence parameters, i.e., k and ε, on the simulation results. For example, in the simulation of density currents (Ikari and Gotoh, 2018), it was found that small initial turbulence eddy viscosity led to steep density variation of the interface and relatively large initial turbulence was required to reproduce the deposit density variation. By simulating the solitary wave propagating over a barrier, Wang and Liu (2020) recommended the initial TKE to be in the range of O (10−10) to O (10−8) m2/s2.

The imposition of the turbulent wall boundary is important in k-ε turbulence modelling. The strategy of specifying the velocity on boundary particles according to the log-law wall function has been adopted (Issa et al., 2010, Ferrand et al., 2013, Tang et al., 2020). The semi-analytical wall boundary (Ferrand et al., 2013), due to its feature in evaluating derivatives near the wall, could impose ∂k/∂n = 0 in the vicinity of the wall. Leroy et al. (2014) further developed the boundary condition for ε. Wang and Liu (2020) proposed an adaptive approach to select appropriate eddy viscosity calculations for high- and low-turbulence bottom boundary regions. On the free surface, no specific boundary conditions for k and ε have been set in the particle-based simulation framework, as suggested by Violeau and Issa (2007), as well as Wang and Liu (2020).

3.3.2. LES model

The LES resolves fluid motions to a prescribed scale (e.g., the particle or mesh size) and adopts an SPS (analogous to SGS or Sub-Grid-Scale in mesh methods) model to capture the important small-scale physical processes that occur at length-scales not adequately resolved on computational particles. Gotoh et al. (2001) pioneered and established the general strategy of implementing the SPS model in particle methods. The SPS flow features were described by the SPS stress tensor. For closure purpose, the linear eddy viscosity model based on the Boussinesq hypothesis (stipulating that the turbulent stress is related to the mean velocity gradients in a similar way as that of the viscous stress) has been widely used and one of the commonly used forms is(8)τijtρ=2νtSij−23kδijwhere Sij represents a component of the filtered strain rate tensor S, k signifies the turbulent kinetic energy and νt stands for the turbulent eddy viscosity that can be estimated by the Smagorinsky model (Smagorinsky, 1963) as(9)νt=(CSΔ)2|S|where Cs denotes the Smagorinsky constant (usually set in between 0.1 to 0.15), Δ stands for the characteristic length scale often considered as the particle size, and |S| implies the local strain rate evaluated as 2S:ST (the double dot product of S and its transpose). The above equations have been extensively used in the projection-based particle methods for the reproduction of coastal breaking waves (Shao and Gotoh, 2004, Shao and Gotoh, 2005, Shao and Ji, 2006) and oil spill (Shimizu et al., 2020). In the ISPH simulation with a blended source term, Gui et al. (2013) showed that the overprediction of the dambreak pressure in a nonturbulent simulation was improved by the inclusion of the SPS modelling. This study used a Smagorinsky constant of 0.25 and such a large value may introduce excessive dissipation, considerably larger than the physical dissipation induced by real turbulence.

SPH models fluids as weakly compressible and the eddy viscosity model taking heat flux into account has been adopted (Blin et al., 2003, Dalrymple and Rogers, 2006)(10)τijtρ=2νtSij−23kδij−δij23CIΔ2|S|2where the constant parameter CI is taken to be 0.0066, and all the other parameters are determined in the same way as those in Eq. (8). This eddy viscosity model has been implemented in SPH open source codes like SPHysics (Gomez-Gesteira et al., 2012), DualSPHysics (Crespo et al., 2015) and GPUSPH (Wei et al., 2015). It is noteworthy that in an SPH simulation (Lowe et al., 2019) (based on DualSPHysics) in which no turbulence model was incorporated, the authors have calculated the time-averaged TKE and found that a no-turbulence-closure SPH simulation over-predicted the TKE.

In particle-based simulations of ocean and coastal wave hydrodynamics that have adopted SPS turbulence modelling, Eqs. (8) and (10) are usually implemented as a routine operation. It should be noted that a sufficient resolution is required to capture important small-scale turbulent components, without satisfying which the SPS modelling would make no effect on the simulation results. Mayrhofer et al. (2015) have conducted very high-resolution simulations of turbulent channel flows and the single Taylor-Green vortex, suggesting that the SPH-based LES simulation of anisotropic turbulence would require a 16-times finer resolution compared to an Eulerian based simulation. In the ISPH simulation of Wang and Liu (2020), the authors also questioned the reliability of the particle-based LES simulations using relatively coarse resolutions. More research efforts probing into this issue would be instructive.

A more precise form of the LES modelling in the framework of SPH is provided by Di Mascio et al. (2017), in which a rigorous reformulation of LES in the context of SPH was presented through using both space and time filtering. This approach leads to the preservation of the Lagrangian structure of the NS equations as material derivatives are being computed on particles that move with the filtered velocity. The LES-SPH of Di Mascio et al. (2017) was rigorously validated through the reproduction of the decay of 2D and 3D homogeneous and isotropic turbulence. Recently, this LES-SPH has been extended by Antuono et al. (2021a) through the incorporation of PST (Particle Shifting Technology) to ensure stability/accuracy for a wide range of Reynolds number flows. The LES-SPH model of Di Mascio et al. (2017) has also been applied in coastal engineering applications such as solitary wave interaction with submerged barriers (Tripepi et al., 2020).

The reproduction of the turbulent wall boundary is also crucially important for reliable turbulence modelling, which requires finer particle resolutions than those away from the wall boundary. To address this, the multi-resolution scheme can be applied. However, no such application to the boundary layer has been documented to date. An alternative strategy is to impose the log-law mean velocity profile in the vicinity of the wall. This strategy has been receiving interest in open channel flow simulations (Arai et al., 2012, Mayrhofer et al., 2015, Kazemi et al., 2017, Kazemi et al., 2020), yet, very few particle-based simulations have adopted this approach for ocean and coastal engineering problems and one of the reported studies is that conducted by Tran-Duc et al. (2019).

3.4. Aerated flow and bubble dynamics

Breaking waves may cause air entrainments or entrapments that have strong effects on local fluid features such as turbulence and impact pressure. Numerical challenges of simulating such phenomena include large deformations, sharp property change at the water-air interface, and accurate modelling of the real fluid compressibility. The latest particle method technologies can handle the fluid interface effectively, while developments are still needed for the precise modelling of real fluid compressibility. Although there has been no rigorous particle-based simulation on air entrainment induced by breaking waves, simulations on relatively well-controlled bubble fields (e.g., a single circular/spherical bubble or air pocket confined in a chamber) have been reported. A milestone work dealing with the water-air interfacial flow is Colagrossi and Landrini (2003), in which both water and air were modelled as weakly compressible fluids. The rising of a single air bubble (Sussman et al., 1994) and the dambreak flow with an entrapped air pocket (Zhou et al., 1999) (a similar process to a moving bore in coastal water) were simulated successfully. Dao (2010) developed a two-phase SPH model and studied the effects of air entrapment on the formation, breaking and post-breaking processes of plunging waves in deep water. Fonty et al. (2020) presented a two-phase mixture SPH scheme with open boundaries for high-density-ratio multiphase flows and showed its effectiveness in modelling the air entrainment in a stepped spillway, a plunging jet and a 3D industrial case of discharge-control structure.

For the dambreak case, Colagrossi and Landrini (2003) analyzed the air pocket pressure and its cushion effect on the collapse of overturning water. A single-phase simulation ignoring the air phase led to an unphysically large impact peak, which was caused by the sudden drop of water above the vacuum pocket area. Luo et al. (2016b) simulated this case by using the two-phase CPM model that imposes continuity conditions on the water-air interface and models the real air compressibility based on thermodynamics. The peak pressure corresponding to the formation of the air pocket predicted by CPM was in better agreement with the experimental data compared to Colagrossi and Landrini (2003) and the unphysically large pressure peak was avoided. Lind et al. (2016) also studied the case by using a coupled ISPH-SPH model. The amplitude of the impact pressure during the existence of the air pocket was similar to that in Colagrossi and Landrini (2003), but the pressure history showed different oscillation features. Recently, Rezavand et al. (2020) studied the dambreak case by a multi-phase WCSPH model. The wave profiles were well captured with a sharp water-air interface and the impact pressure was satisfactorily predicted. These studies confirmed the existence of the air's cushion effect on wave impacts, but could not tell precisely the dynamic responses of the air pocket and their effect on the nearby pressure field. Luo et al. (2016b) and Luo and Koh (2017) have conducted wave impact experiments in a connected container, in which violent sloshing occurs in the left big tank and applies a force to the right narrow tank that can be seen as an enclosed air pocket. The oscillation of the air pocket pressure and the synchronous features of nearby water pressures were measured and reproduced by the CPM model accurately. This study provides pertinent benchmark data for water-air two-phase flow models.

The bubble rising is another well-received benchmark example to test the stability and accuracy of two-phase flow models. By using SPH, the rising and merging of 2D bubbles have been studied (Grenier et al., 2013, Yang et al., 2020c). Zhang et al. (2015) conducted 3D simulations of the rising of a single bubble and the coalescences of two bubbles approaching in different directions. To save computational time for 3D simulations, Li et al. (2020b) have developed an SPH model of the cylindrical coordinate that allows the simulation of only part of the whole domain by utilizing the axisymmetric feature of the bubble rising problem. In the category of incompressible particle methods, Zainali et al. (2013) studied the 2D bubble rising in viscous and viscoelastic liquids based on a two-phase ISPH model. Duan et al. (2017a) studied the 2D and 3D bubble rising by using a two-phase MPS model. By introducing the boiling phase change into a coupled MPS-SPH model, Duan et al. (2020) simulated the boiling-generated bubbles and their morphological evolutions.

More often, a cluster of small bubbles, i.e., bubbly flow, rather than a single or several large bubbles are formed. Compared to the scenario of a small number of large-size bubbles, the bubbly flow is much more challenging to simulate because of the high complexity of the underlying physics and the stringent requirement on particle resolution to discretize small bubbles. Few relevant studies have been documented in the literature to date. An important study is that by Grenier et al. (2013) who simulated the rising and evolution of a set of 36 bubbles (mimicking the oil-water separation process) and analyzed the influence of surface tension on the separation process. The bubbly flow involves complex turbulence structures and multi-phase interaction, the potential of particle methods in resolving which needs to be further explored.

Strong bubble compression/expansion can happen in cavitation or underwater explosion. Particle-based modelling of this process, especially in capturing the strong compressibility, is challenging. Research efforts addressing this problem have been reported recently. Pineda et al. (2019) have simulated the 2D bubble collapses in the free field and near a rigid surface by developing an SPH-ALE (arbitrary Lagrangian-Eulerian) model with the gas phase described by the stiffened gas equation of state (Ivings et al., 1998). The pressure waves and micro-jets associated with cavitation were predicted, and the influences of the distance between the bubble and the wall were examined. By developing an SPH axisymmetric solver, Joshi et al. (2019) have studied the collapse of a single cavitation bubble close to an elastic-plastic material and the induced material erosion. Sun et al. (2021b) have extended the δ-SPH for strongly-compressible bubbles by incorporating the energy equation and proposing a new technique of particle splitting/merging (to cope with the strong variation of particle volume). The morphological evolution and velocity/pressure fields of underwater-explosion bubbles have been well captured. The 3D axisymmetric underwater-explosion bubbles have been also simulated by extending the δ-SPH to the cylindrical coordinates (Sun et al., 2021c). In Peng et al. (2021a), a particle regeneration technique invoking background particles has been proposed to address the particle disorders during strong compression. Several benchmark examples of air cavity and bubble collapse have been studied.

3.5. Oil spill under wave/current actions

The oil spill has also been simulated by particle methods. In the context of weakly-compressible methods, Violeau et al. (2007) studied the leakage mechanism of heavy, light and emulsion oils with the containment of a floating rigid boom in two conditions, i.e., steady currents and regular waves. Shi et al. (2018a) studied the oil spill contained by a flexible floating boom using a multi-phase SPH model. The evolution of oil slick and the associated vorticity distributions under current-only and combined wave-current conditions were examined. The comparison of the containment effects of flexible and rigid booms has indicated that the flexible boom is less effective.

In the context of projection particle methods, Jeong et al. (2013) studied the oil leakage from 2D damaged tanks with holes on the side or bottom wall. The predicted oil height loss was analyzed in comparison with theoretical solutions. Duan et al. (2017b) studied the spreading of an oil slick initially placed on the top corner of a reservoir and the continuous oil spill from a damaged tank. In the former case, the effect of waves on the spreading of oil slick was investigated; in the latter case, the variation of the spreading and spilling rates with the hole size was examined. The oil spill case has also been studied in Shimizu et al. (2020) based on a multiphase ISPH model that incorporates the SPS oil-water mixing and the surface tension simultaneously. Using the model, the authors have also studied the oil movement under breaking waves by comparing experimental snapshots in Wei et al. (2016b).

4. Wave/current interaction with structures

Waves interact with ocean and coastal structures of various types. The resulting wave loads, runup and overtopping, and the induced structural motion or deformation are important design factors. Particle methods have been extensively used for the wave-structure interaction (WSI) problems in ocean and coastal engineering. Numerical developments for boundary modelling, energy conservation and spurious pressure fluctuation suppression enhance the accuracy of WSI simulation. More numerical details are referred to in the recent reviews for fluid-structure interaction (Zhang et al., 2017a, Liu and Zhang, 2019). This section does not extensively discuss the computational algorithms but instead focuses on the recent applications of particle methods in WSI. According to the level of numerical difficulty, the WSI studies are reviewed in four categories, i.e., fixed rigid structures, moving rigid structures, deformable structures and permeable structures. After that, particle-based WSI advances in selected subjects of sloshing and marine renewable energy devices are discussed.

In the WSI problems with moving structures, the change of either domain affects the other. To model the coupling effects, there are two major strategies, i.e., the monolithic approach solving both domains simultaneously (strongly-coupled) (Gee et al., 2011) and the partitioned approach solving both domains separately (loosely-coupled). The latter approach prevails in particle-based WSI simulations owing to its ease of implementation and flexibilities to couple particle methods with other well-established structural solvers. An intuitive also the most standard implementation of the partitioned coupling treats structural particles with position/velocity information as the boundary for fluid solver and integrates pressures on structural boundaries (normally from the fluid solution) to get the excitation force for structural analysis. The two solvers can propagate in time synchronously without information exchange in a single time step or sequentially with the fluid domain solved first and the solved fluid variables then transferred to the structural domain. These are the conventional parallel staggered (CPS) and conventional sequential staggered (CSS) schemes, respectively (Farhat and Lesoinne, 2000). The standard CSS coupling has been frequently used in particle-based simulations especially those coupling particle methods with FEM. Fourey et al. (2017) compared the performances of CPS and CSS based on cases with deformable structures and suggested that CSS is more stable while CPS is more efficient. Note that in the framework of CPS or CSS, the prediction-correction or iteration schemes can be used to increase accuracy such as the Symplectic integration scheme in Zhan et al. (2019).

4.1. Fixed rigid structures

Practical examples of wave interaction with fixed rigid structures include the wave impact on fixed breakwaters, seawalls, and oil/gas platforms. In simulations, the structure boundaries can be treated in similar ways as those for fixed computational boundaries and hence do not introduce extra numerical difficulties except that structures of complex shape (Adami et al., 2012, Chiron et al., 2019) or small thickness (Meringolo et al., 2015) need special treatments.
