For wave interaction with fixed coastal structures, numerous works have studied the laboratory scale cases such as the solitary wave impact on coastal houses (Liang et al., 2010), wave dissipation by perforated breakwater (Meringolo et al., 2015), wave overtopping (Sasani Babak and Akbari, 2019, Mokos et al., 2020). Realistic-scale modelling has been conducted by using the GPU parallelized DualSPHysics. For example, Barreiro et al. (2013) simulated the propagation of a real-life incoming wave and its interaction with a sea walk. Altomare et al. (2014) conducted 3D simulations of regular wave actions on a real rubble mound breakwater. The computed wave run-ups were in reasonable agreement with experimental data and empirical formulae, for regular waves of surf similarity numbers from 3.0 to 5.5. Altomare et al. (2015a) simulated the sea wave impacts on coastal structures with vertical quay and storm return wall. The numerical results of wave elevation and wave impact force were validated against formulae predictions.

The tsunami wave that can be very disastrous to coastal area has been studied extensively. Based on GPUSPH, Wei et al. (2015) studied the tsunami bore impact on bridge piers, focusing on the flow field and bed shear stress around the pier and the hydrodynamic loading on the pier, as well as their correlation with the pier shape and orientation. Followed by this study, Wei and Dalrymple (2016) studied the tsunami impacts on bridge superstructures and examined the effectiveness of two measures, i.e., up-wave service road bridge and offshore breakwater, in mitigating tsunami actions. By using the δ-SPH, Aristodemo et al. (2017) studied the solitary-wave induced force on submerged horizontal circular cylinders (with experimental validations). The hydrodynamic coefficients in the empirical formula for estimating horizontal and vertical forces were calibrated and applied to analyze the drag, inertia and lift force components. The authors also studied the solitary interaction with a square barrier (Tripepi et al., 2020), focusing on the semi-analytical estimation of the horizontal loads. Through applying the SPH open source DualSPHysics, Pringgana et al. (2021) investigated the influence of onshore structures' orientations and arrangements during a tsunami impact. Harris et al. (2021) presented the development and engineering application of a double-point MPM formulation to investigate solitary wave interaction with permeable seawalls and plane beaches.

For the projection-based methods, Luo et al. studied the solitary wave interaction with seawalls (Luo et al., 2019) and breakwaters (Ren et al., 2019) using CPM. Wang et al. (2020) studied the overtopping on a sloping sea dike induced by a single and two successive solitary waves using MPS. The influence of the interaction between successive solitary waves on the overtopping pattern was examined. Divya et al. (2020) presented an application of MLPG_R for wave-vegetation interaction, in which the vegetation was modelled using rigid cylindrical/strip type structures.

Also studied extensively is the wave slamming on fixed ocean structures. For example, Gao et al. (2012) studied the regular wave slamming on a deck platform by using a corrected WCSPH model. Domínguez et al. (2013) simulated a violent wave impact on a realistic oil platform using 109 particles. Ni et al. (2014) studied the regular wave interaction with 2D and 3D wave barriers by using an SPH model with a modified dynamic solid boundary treatment. The air phase is believed to affect the wave slamming loads. In this regard, Lind et al. (2015) simulated the wave slamming on a fixed flat plate using an ISPH-WCSPH two-phase flow model. The results affirmed the air cushion effect for impact onto flat water, which reduced with the increases of the ratio of wave height to wavelength. In Rafiee et al. (2015), the wave impact on a vertical wall with an entrapped air pocket was studied by using a two-phase flow model based on SPH-ALE formulations, and the evolution of the air pocket and the associated velocity/pressure fields were discussed. Sun et al. (2019d) have studied the freak wave impact on a fixed box-shape structure with air entrapment by using a two-phase δ+-SPH model. Satisfactorily predicted are the morphological evolution of the entrapped air pocket (the top plots of Fig. 3), the violent slamming pressures at the wave impingement stage (the left-bottom plot of Fig. 3), and the negative pressures at the water-exit (wave receding) stage (the right-bottom plot of Fig. 3). The wave slamming pressure showed oscillations in the experiment, which have not been fully captured by the two-phase δ+-SPH model. To tackle this problem further, more precise modelling of the dynamic interaction between the incident wave and entrapped air is needed. Recently, Zhai et al. (2021) simulated the wave impact on a fixed ocean structure with columns and slab by using a GPU-accelerated SPH model, and investigated the influences of structural columns on the flow state, impact pressure and wave energy transmission.

The wave/flow interacting with cylinders is another topic of substantial research efforts. Based on the δ-SPH, Marrone et al. (2013) simulated the 2D steady flows passing through horizontal cylinders at Reynolds numbers ranging from 10 to 2400. Bouscasse et al. (2017) studied the flow interaction with cylinders near or intersecting the free surface. The characteristics of vortex generation, mixing process, free surface breaking and drag/lift forces were clarified under various Froude numbers and submergence conditions. Sun et al. (2017a) simulated flow passing rectangular, circular and elliptical cylinders using the δ+-SPH model. This model was further enhanced by the tensile instability control scheme in Sun et al. (2018b), which was applied to simulate flow passing objects at Reynolds number reaching 10,000. The vorticity and negative pressure in the wake regions were accurately reproduced. By comparing the results produced by three well-established solvers (one of which was the δ+-SPH), Colagrossi et al. (2019) demonstrated the reliability of three cases of viscous flow interacting with submerged circular cylinder as benchmarks. Negi et al. (2020) studied the flow past a circular cylinder at Reynolds numbers of 20 and 200 by using SPH with an improved non-reflecting outlet boundary. The feature of the model in using an order of magnitude fewer particles was highlighted. Through rewriting NS equations in the ALE formalism and incorporating the diffusive terms of δ-SPH in equations of density and mass, Antuono et al. (2021b) developed a so-called δ-ALE-SPH and showed its effectiveness in several test cases including the flow past an inclined elliptical cylinder.

For vertical cylinders that necessitate 3D simulations, Jian et al. (2017) studied the wave run-up on a surging cylinder in regular waves using WCSPH (with experimental validations) and examined the maximum run-up under different wave steepness, wave scattering and surge amplitudes. Chow et al. (2019) utilized the single-GPU accelerated ISPH model to study the focused wave impact on a vertical cylinder. The effect of breaking waves in amplifying the local pressures near the water surface has been highlighted. The focused wave interaction with a vertical cylinder has been simulated by Zhang et al. (2020d) (by a model coupling SPH and a FEM-based FNPT solver) and Agarwal et al. (2021) (by a model coupling MLPG_R and a FEM-based FNPT solver).

4.2. Moving rigid structures

Most structures in the sea are not fixed. Practical examples include floating breakwaters, floating oil/gas platforms, floating wind turbines, ships, and the vortex-induced vibrations of marine risers/cables. Among the various options of fluid-structure coupling schemes, the CSS (conventional sequential staggered) scheme has been used in most documented particle-based simulations due to its ease of implementation. In the following, the recent efforts towards the reliable simulation of moving rigid structures will be reviewed.

The floating breakwater and seawall have attracted much interest in recent years. Regarding moving seawalls, Liang et al. (2017) conducted an ISPH-based simulation of solitary wave interactions with spring-controlled movable seawall with particular attention on seawall movement, wave runup height and hydrodynamic loading. As for floating breakwaters, Ren et al. (2015) simulated the dynamic response of a freely floating rectangular box under nonlinear waves by using a WCSPH model with an enhanced moving boundary scheme and a structural force evaluation scheme. The authors then extended this model by incorporating modules describing the tension and slack of mooring cables in Ren et al. (2017) and simulated the wave interaction with a submerged floating breakwater (Peng et al., 2013). The influences of the immersion depth and the length and density of the breakwater on wave dissipation and structural responses were examined. Ardianti et al. (2017) simulated the tsunami wave interaction on moored shelters using a coupled model with SPH for the fluid and structure and DEM (Discrete Element Method) for the mooring cables. The forces and shelter motions induced by the tsunami wave were predicted reasonably well. Domínguez et al. (2019b) extended the DualSPHysics by incorporating the mooring dynamics open source MoorDyn (Hall and Goupee, 2015) and studied the regular wave interaction with freely and moored floating boxes. Based on the coupled DualSPHysics-MoorDyn model, Liu et al. (2019) studied the wave dissipation properties of winged box-shape (with protruding plats at the corners) floating breakwaters; Liu and Wang (2020b) compared the wave attenuation performances of floating breakwaters of different cross-sectional shapes under various wave conditions; Liu and Wang (2020a) investigated the performances of several configurations of box-shape floating breakwaters.

For the floating ocean structures, Rudman and his co-authors simulated the freak wave impact on tension leg platforms based on a 3D WCSPH model. The effects of wave incidence angle and mooring line tension on platform motions (Rudman and Cleary, 2013) and the effects of mooring system on platform motions and morning tensions (Rudman and Cleary, 2016) were examined. Zheng et al. (2018a) studied the green water impact on a floating deck by using a 2D ISPH model (with experimental validations). Gunn et al. (2018) studied the wave interaction with a tethered buoy by a 3D WCSPH model (with experimental validations) and gave suggestions on particle resolutions to capture the WSI process. Rijas and Sriram (2019) studied the nonlinear waves produced by forced heave motions of 2D mono and twin hulls by using the MLPG_R method. The marine risers/cables, as important components of oil-gas platforms, are suffering from the issue of vortex-induced vibration. To shed light on this problem, Sun et al. (2019a) conducted 2D simulations of the motions of rectangular and circular sections in currents.

The water entry of marine structures is always associated with intensive impact forces (Vandamme et al., 2011) and has been the subject of substantial studies. The modelling of the transient process and the prediction of the slamming pressures have been facilitated by various numerical enhancements such as the particle shifting scheme (Skillen et al., 2013), the improved boundary modelling (Liu et al., 2014, Amicarelli et al., 2015, Sun et al., 2015a), the δ-SPH scheme (Sun et al., 2018a), and the Riemann solver (Yang et al., 2020b). After the structure body enters fluid, an air cavity is enclosed by the jet splashes on both sides of the body. The modelling of the air cavity necessitates the inclusion of the air phase in simulation. For this, Yan et al. (2015) presented a two-phase SPH model. The simulation of a wedge entry suggested that the influences of air on the acceleration of and the pressure exerted on a free-falling wedge are small because the air can escape easily as the wedge slams the water. Khayyer and Gotoh (2016) presented a novel scheme referred to CIECS (Compressible-Incompressible Error Compensating Source) for projection particle methods and presented enhanced predictions of wave slamming pressures through water entry examples of rigid plates. Gong et al. (2016) found that the two-phase simulation can well predict the entire water entry process, while the single-phase simulation can only capture the flow features before the formation of the cavity. Ma et al. (2018) examined the influences of the density ratio (between water and wedge) and Froude number on the pinch-off time, pinch-off location and shape of the wedge-entry-induced cavity. Yang et al. (2020b) studied the flat plate slamming and the water entry of a catamaran, suggesting that for structures with a deep deadrise angle, the air phase can reduce the impact load and hence protect the water entry structure.

The wave-ship interaction has been extensively studied with focuses on different aspects such as the ship-sailing induced breaking waves (Landrini et al., 2012, Marrone et al., 2012), wave-induced ship motions in severe water-shipping conditions (Kawamura et al., 2016), and wave slamming loads during ship hull entry (Cheng et al., 2020). The responses of damaged ships in the sea have recently attracted much interest. In this direction, Cheng et al. (2017) studied the flooding and sinking process of a damaged ship with an opening. The inflow jet from the opening and the highly deformed sloshing flows in the flooded cabin, as well as their effects on the ship's sinking path, were systematically examined. In the follow-up works, Cao et al. (2018) took into account the air phase in the flooded cabin, observing that the air decreased the dynamic moment induced by the flooding flow and the sinking rate of the ship. The dynamic sinking process in wave conditions was further studied in Ming et al. (2018) and Cao et al. (2019). Cheng et al. (2019) simulated the ditching of a real-scale ground-effect wing ship and investigated the kinematic and dynamic features during the ditching. Zhang et al. (2020c) studied the flooding of a 2D freely-floating damaged ship using the MPS method. Recently, Tagliafierro et al. (2021) conducted an interesting study using SPH for performance assessment of a planing hull, showing the robustness of SPH in reproducing the 3D flow around a planing hull including spray structures.

Many other applications involve wave interaction with moving structures, i.e., liquid sloshing in moving tanks, wave energy converters, etc. We will discuss them in more detail in Section 4.5 as exemplary cases of particle method applications in ocean/coastal engineering.

4.3. Deformable structures

Real structures are not infinitely rigid and are subjected to structural deformations and stresses under wave actions. The structural responses may couple with the incident wave to trigger unwanted dynamic amplification when the frequency of structural response is close to that of the wave action. Hence, it is crucially important to take structural dynamics into account in analyzing this kind of WSI problems. From the numerical point of view, this is a water-solid two-phase flow problem whose major numerical issues include two aspects: 1) accurate description of each phase; 2) coupling of both phases with a proper imposition of the continuity conditions on the structural boundary, i.e., fluid-solid interface. The particle method community has recently dedicated significant efforts to these issues and the major strategies are reviewed below.

In most of the recent research works, a Newtonian framework has been considered, in which the governing equations for the solid phase correspond to conservation equations of linear and angular momenta. The linear momentum equation is presented here for illustration:(11)DuiSDt=1ρS∂σijS∂xj+gi+FiFSρSwhere uiS and ρS represent the velocity and density of a solid particle, respectively; FiFS denotes the force applied on the solid particle from nearby fluid particles; σijS signifies the stresses of the solid particle. The most-up-to-date particle technologies can solve the governing equations with generally good accuracy and hence the first challenge mentioned above, i.e., accurate description of each phase, can be managed satisfactorily well, provided that consistent/accurate differential operator models, as well as proper constitutive equations for solid phase, are incorporated (Khayyer et al., 2018a).

To handle the second challenge, i.e., the coupling between fluid and structure, the partitioned coupling approach has been dominantly used. Key aspects of the partitioned coupling are the modelling of the actions from one phase to another and the imposition of the motion/stress continuity conditions at the structural boundary. To tackle these, two primary approaches have been adopted. The first approach is the so-called pressure integration (PI) approach (Antoci et al., 2007), in which the pressures on the structural boundary segment covered by the structural particle's influence domain are integrated to get the action of fluids to a structural particle, i.e., FiFS in Eq. (11). The stress continuity is applied by setting the action from a structural particle to its symmetrically linked fluid particle to be -FiFS (Antoci et al., 2007). The second approach is the Fluid Structure Acceleration (FSA) coupling approach (Khayyer et al., 2018a), in which the acceleration of a structural particle is evaluated by including the effects of fluid particles in the target structural particle's influence domain (Oger et al., 2009, Khayyer et al., 2018a). Khayyer et al. (2018a) illustrated that the pressure gradient terms (the major driving factor of acceleration) for a pair of fluid and structural particles are equal in magnitude and opposite in direction, implying the normal stress continuity at the structure-fluid interface. For both approaches, the motion continuity can be established by including the kinematic information of the structural particles (treated as boundary particles for the fluid domain in the partitioned coupling) in the fluid solver. The FSA approach has been proven robust, especially for long-duration simulations, and seems to be prevailing in particle-based simulations of deformable structures characterized by homogeneous density. For hydroelastic FSI simulations corresponding to laminated composite structures, Khayyer et al. (2021b) have used a PI-based coupling. It is noteworthy that a crucially important criterion in assessing the reliability of a fluid-structure coupling scheme is the energy conservation property, which has been investigated by Khayyer et al. (Khayyer et al., 2018a, Khayyer et al., 2021a, Khayyer et al., 2021b) and Hermange et al. (2019b).

Based on the methods used for fluid and structure, the major research works of particle-based simulation of WSI problems can be categorized into two main groups, i.e., entirely Lagrangian meshfree methods (where particle methods, i.e., Lagrangian & meshfree methods, are employed for both fluid and structure) or partially Lagrangian meshfree methods (where a particle method is applied only for one phase and the other phase, e.g., the structure phase, is solved by another method such as FEM). As for entirely Lagrangian meshfree methods, several studies have well presented the potential robustness of particle methods for hydroelastic WSI. Examples include Antoci et al. (2007), Oger et al. (2009), Rafiee and Thiagarajan (2009), Sun et al. (2019c), Zhan et al. (2019), Zhang et al. (2021a), Hwang et al. (2014), Hwang et al. (2016), Wu et al. (2016), Falahaty et al. (2018), Khayyer et al. (2018a), Wang et al. (2019b), Khayyer et al. (2019b), Sun et al. (2019e), Ng et al. (2020), Sun et al. (2020), Sun et al. (2021a), Zha et al. (2021) and Morikawa and Asai (2021). Regarding the second category, i.e., partially Lagrangian meshfree methods, examples include Sriram and Ma (2012), Fourey et al. (2017), Long et al. (2017), Shi et al. (2018b), Zhang and Wan (2018b), Zhang et al. (2019a), Sun et al. (2019f), Hermange et al. (2019b), Hu et al. (2019), Zhang et al. (2019b), Zhang et al. (2019c), Zhang et al. (2020e), Sun et al. (2021d), Peng et al. (2021b), Zhang et al. (2021c) and Long et al. (2021).

As for validation of particle-based WSI methods, several widely-adopted benchmark test cases include the hydrostatic water column on an elastic plate (Fourey et al., 2017), dambreak with an elastic gate (Antoci et al., 2007), dambreak with an elastic barrier (Idelsohn et al., 2008a, Liao et al., 2015), and dambreak with elastic wall (Sun et al., 2015b). In these studies, Sun et al. (2019c) took the air phase into account, achieving a water-air-deformable solid three-phase simulation. The simulation results showed the significant effect of the entrapped air pocket on the flow evolution and on the hydrodynamic load being exerted on deformable structures.

For applications in ocean engineering, the sloshing with hanging or bottom clamped elastic baffles (Idelsohn et al., 2008b) has been extensively studied (Hwang et al., 2014, Hwang et al., 2016, Falahaty et al., 2018, Khayyer et al., 2018a, Hu et al., 2019, Khayyer et al., 2019b, Ng et al., 2020, Zhang et al., 2020e, Sun et al., 2021a). In these studies, the deformation of the baffles and their mitigation effects on sloshing waves have been investigated. Zhang and Wan (2018b) have studied the violent sloshing waves in an elastic tank and examined the effects of wall stiffness on the evolution of sloshing waves, impact pressures, and structural responses. The authors have pointed out that the observed pressure fluctuations were attributed to the dynamic vibration of the elastic walls. Recent studies have clearly presented the stresses in deformable structures (e.g., see the left plot of Fig. 4), yet, there have been no quantitative comparisons of reproduced stress field in sloshing simulations due to the lack of experimental data. Another subject attracting substantial research efforts is the hydroelastic slamming of water entry objects such as elastic wedge (Scolan, 2004, Oger et al., 2009, Khayyer et al., 2018a, Khayyer et al., 2019b, Wang et al., 2019b, Zhang et al., 2019c, Sun et al., 2020, Zhang et al., 2021c) and marine panel (Stenius et al., 2013, Fourey et al., 2017, Falahaty et al., 2018, Khayyer et al., 2018a, Hermange et al., 2019b, Khayyer et al., 2019b).

Among the research contributions of particle-based simulation of hydroelastic FSI, the works by Khayyer and his co-authors are presented herein for illustration. Fig. 4 shows the results by two entirely Lagrangian meshfree methods, namely, ISPH-SPH (Khayyer et al., 2018a) and MPS-MPS (Khayyer et al., 2019b). In both cases, the FSA coupling scheme is applied and structural models are formulated in the Newtonian framework similar to the fluid ones. Results by both solvers are qualitatively comparable, featured by the integrity of particle distributions at the fluid-structure interface (without the presence of an unphysical gap that may appear in absence of a reliable coupling scheme). The presented snapshot of the MPS-MPS method (Khayyer et al., 2019b) corresponds to a multi-resolution (MR) scheme. Khayyer et al. (2021b) have developed a coupled ISPH-HSPH (Hamiltonian SPH) method and shown its superior energy conservation feature. This method has been applied to the simulation of composite elastic structures and their interactions with incompressible fluid flow, including the hydroelastic slamming of composite marine panels. In a recent study, Khayyer et al. (2021a) have presented an Enhanced multi-resolution ISPH-SPH hydroelastic FSI model, and elaborated its accuracy and energy conservation property in modelling hydroelastic problems of sloshing with clamped elastic baffle and dam break on an elastic plate.

Some other ocean engineering problems involving deformable structures have also been simulated by particle methods. For example, Sun et al. (2019e) studied the solitary wave interaction with moored deformable plates, focusing on the effects of the plate stiffness on plate motions and wave pressures applied on the plate. Zhang et al. (2019a) simulated the regular wave impacting a fixed horizontal suspended plate and examined the effect of structural flexibility on the wave impact pressure. Zhang et al. (2021a) have simulated the passive flapping of a flexible fish-like body in current flows, studying the deformation and trajectory of the body, as well as the induced vorticities. Sun et al. (2021a) have simulated the viscous flow around a fixed circular cylinder with an elastic plate. The vorticities of the fluid flows, as well as the deflection and stresses of the plate have been elaborated.

While the above studies have all been conducted in 2D, 3D particle-based simulations of deformable structures have been reported recently. Zhang and Wan (2018a) have developed a 3D MPS-FEM model. This model was later applied to simulate the violent sloshing in an elastic tank in Chen et al. (2019). The influence of the stiffness of the wall on the sloshing characteristics and structural responses were studied. Hermange et al. (2019a) have presented a 3D SPH-FEM model and simulated the case of sloshing with a bottom clamped elastic baffle. Based on the 3D GPUSPH, Paquier et al. (2021) have studied the seagrass movements under wave-current conditions and showed that the model can be used to estimate the Manning's coefficient (roughness friction) for coastal vegetation.

4.4. Permeable structures

A considerable percentage of the world's coastal structures (e.g., breakwaters and sea walls) consists of mounds or layers of quarried rock fill (Van der Meer et al., 2018). The permeable components stimulate the dissipation of incident wave energy through friction and local wave breaking, showing distinct behaviors from those of wave interaction with impermeable structures as discussed above.

To simulate the wave interaction with permeable structures, the microscopic approach that models the interstitial flows explicitly can be used. This strategy is able to predict the pore-scale flow features, however, would be impractical for real structures due to the prohibitive computational time. Another strategy is the macroscopic simulation (Hsu et al., 2002, Lin and Karunarathna, 2007) that focuses on the mean flow parameters such as wave dissipation, reflection, transmission and overtopping. The documented particle-based simulations primarily adopted this strategy by solving the volume-averaged (Shao, 2010, Akbari and Namin, 2013) or mixture-theory-based (Peng et al., 2017, Khayyer et al., 2018b, Wen et al., 2020a) NS equations. Kazemi et al. (2019) have elaborated a theoretical justification on the applicability of the macroscopic equations in particle-based simulations, which led to constraints on the computational resolution near the interface, as well as the radii of the support domains for porosity calculation and for particle interpolation of the governing equations. A sensitivity analysis on the computational resolution was conducted based on the case of solitary wave run-up on porous breakwaters (Jensen et al., 2015).

In the macroscopic simulation of porous media flows, the retarding effect of solid skeleton fluid motion is described by empirical force terms. The empirical formulation has been advanced by introducing more physics, starting from the linear viscous force that dominates in laminar flows (Bear, 2013), to including the nonlinear drag for turbulent flows (Sollitt and Cross, 1972), and to adding a third term to bridge the transition from laminar to turbulent flow (Lin and Karunarathna, 2007). The selection of the empirical coefficients in the force terms is also very important for reliable modelling. These coefficients can be calibrated experimentally (Van Gent, 1995, Venkataraman and Rao, 1998) or analytically (Du Plessis, 1994, Wu et al., 2007). A comprehensive review of the frictional force models has been presented in Losada et al. (2016).

The particle methods have been utilized to simulate various problems of wave interaction with permeable structures or media. The pioneering work of Shao (2010) (based on ISPH) successfully captured the wave height, pressure and force in four cases, i.e., the damping of solitary (Huang et al., 2008) and regular (Karunarathna and Lin, 2006) waves over porous beds, solitary wave interaction with submerged porous breakwaters (Huang et al., 2003) and breaking wave overtopping on a caisson breakwater protected by a single layer of porous material (Liu et al., 1999). As a key part of the simulation, the continuities of velocity and stress on the interface of the clear fluid and porous media were imposed on imaginary grids on the interface line. This solving strategy was extended in a subsequent ISPH simulation (Gui et al., 2015) by defining an interface region rather than a line to apply the continuity conditions. The authors simulated the experimental case of solitary wave interaction with a submerged porous breakwater (Wu and Hsiao, 2013) and studied the wave free surface and velocity. This model was further extended in Zhou and Dong (2018) by incorporating the continuity conditions into the pressure equation explicitly (avoiding numerical smoothing near interface). The benchmark example of waves propagating over a porous breakwater of trapezoidal cross section (Hieu and Tanimoto, 2006) was simulated for model validation.

In the framework of the Darcy velocity-based ISPH, Akbari and Namin (2013) proposed the concept of background meshes for calculating the porosities on particles. This concept and its extended versions have been adopted in many later studies. Using the model, the wave running up and overtopping a caisson breakwater were studied. Focused was the role of the porous armor layer in mitigating the fluid velocity and pressure in front of the caisson and reducing overtopping. Akbari (2014) extended this model by introducing the SPS turbulence model (Gotoh et al., 2001) and studied the breaking wave overtopping on a caisson breakwater with multi porous layers (Sakakiyama and Liu, 2001). The authors highlighted the importance of fluid turbulence at the fluid-porous media interface. More recently, Akbari's model has been utilized to investigate the wave-induced movement of a caisson breakwater placed on a permeable bed (Akbari and Taherkhani, 2019) and the wave forces on submarine pipelines over permeable beds (Akbari and Pooyarad, 2020). Also based on ISPH, the density currents over and within porous media have been studied (Basser et al., 2017, Pahar and Dhar, 2017b). Through implementing the concept of apparent density, as used in Akbari (2014), Tsurudome et al. (2020) presented an ISPH-based code for simulations of solitary wave propagation and run-up on permeable beaches.

In the category of WCSPH, Ren et al. (2014) simulated the wave propagating over a trapezoidal porous breakwater (Hieu and Tanimoto, 2006). The SPS turbulence model was implemented for flows outside the porous media. The fluid velocity, vorticity and pressure distribution near the breakwater were analyzed. Ren et al. (2016) then advanced the model by taking into account the turbulence effect in the porous media and studied the wave interaction with two-layer porous breakwaters (Garcia et al., 2004). The velocity distributions and turbulence features for submerged and merged breakwaters were analyzed. The model was extended to 3D in Wen et al. (2018a), which has been utilized to simulate the wave interaction with detached permeable breakwaters. The capability of the model to reproduce 3D breaking waves, spatial circular flows and higher harmonics were highlighted. Recently, Ren and her co-authors incorporated the mixture-theory-based equations into their SPH model. Based on this, Wen et al. (2020a) have studied the wave-induced current in inhomogeneous coral reef regions, focusing on the effects of porosity value, the thickness of the porous layer, and type of porosity distribution; Wen et al. (2020b) have studied the influences of reef degradation on the wave setup, wave-induced current and low-frequency wave energy over the reef flat.

One key and challenging point in simulating wave interaction with porous media is the proper imposition of the continuity conditions of volume, velocity and normal stress at the fluid-porous media interface. For this purpose, the above studies predominantly adopted the means of numerical smoothing near the fluid-porous media interface. Although being beneficial for enhancing numerical stability, this approach smears out some real physics near the interface. To overcome this issue, Khayyer et al. (2018b) have proposed an enhanced ISPH model with a compatible representation of the fluid-porous media interface, achieving an accurate imposition of the velocity/pressure continuity without using any artificial numerical smoothing. Critical validations and analyses have been conducted based on various examples, including the rapid seepage flow in a rockfill dam and wave propagation over a submerged triangular permeable bar, as presented in Fig. 5. The results have illustrated notable volume conservation, regular particle distributions near the interface, and physically smooth pressure distribution.

Fluid turbulence is another important physics in wave interaction with porous structures. Numerical works including or excluding the turbulence model have been presented and the results from both approaches have not shown evident differences in terms of the macroscopic fluid quantities such as wave height and velocity. Indeed, the study of Kazemi et al. (2019) highlighted the lack of reliable data for validating the accuracy of the turbulence modelling especially that near the interfacial boundary. In a follow-up study of this work, i.e., Kazemi et al. (2020), the authors have conducted thorough validations of the turbulence modelling of open channel flow over porous beds. However, few such attempts for oceanic and coastal wave interaction with porous structures have been reported, which deserves more research efforts.

One more noteworthy point is that some porous structures such as the soil embankment undergo deformations (failure happens if deformations are too large) under external excitations. Few particle-based simulations have addressed this process. One important study in this category is that by Bui and Nguyen (2017), who have developed a novel fluid-solid SPH model for flow through deformable porous media and studied the embankment failure induced by seepage flows.

4.5. Two typical wave-structure interaction (WSI) problems in ocean engineering

4.5.1. Liquid sloshing

Liquid sloshing is a critical concern in the design of liquid cargo ships like the LNG (liquefied natural gas) vessels. The liquid sloshing can cause disastrous impact forces or overturning moments, which either induce local damages to the tank structure or trigger global stability issues of the ship. Comprehensive introductions of the physics, theories and numerical technologies of liquid sloshing are referred to Ibrahim (2005), Faltinsen and Timokha (2009) and Ibrahim (2020).

The liquid sloshing involves several critical phenomena such as wave breaking, gas entrapment, and phase transition (between liquid and gas). Besides, there are abundant experimental data based on well-controlled experimental conditions and small-scale tanks. These two reasons make liquid sloshing an ideal benchmark for testing the robustness of particle methods in the aspects of boundary modelling, energy conservation, and pressure noise suppression. In this regard, many works simulated the violent sloshing in rectangular tanks under one degree-of-freedom (1-DOF) translational (Rafiee et al., 2012, Shao et al., 2012, Shimizu et al., 2018, Meng et al., 2020) or rotational (Shao et al., 2012, Chen et al., 2013a, Cao et al., 2014) excitations, and some studied the sloshing under coupled excitations (Cao et al., 2014).

Based on the δ-SPH method, the shallow-water sloshing was studied by Antuono et al. (2012) where a 2D modal method was validated and by Bouscasse et al. (2013a) where a new wave pattern was observed. De Chowdhury and Sannasiraj (2014) studied the high-order harmonics in non-violent sloshing waves, and numerical factors affecting the δ-SPH model in predicting high-order harmonics were parametrically investigated. Green and Peiró (2018) conducted long-duration simulations of sloshing in tanks with low filling ratio and high stretching. By using the δ+-SPH model, Sun et al. (2019b) simulated the shallow water sloshing under 1-DOF translational excitation and the long-duration sloshing under 6-DOF motions. The advantages of the model in alleviating unphysical pressure fluctuations and maintaining volume conservation were demonstrated.

For the projection-based particle methods, Gotoh et al. (2014) studied the violent sloshing induced by 1-DOF translational and rotational excitations by developing an enhanced ISPH model. Zheng et al. (2014) presented an ISPH model with a Rankine source solution, giving good predictions of wave profiles and impact pressures of violent horizontal sloshing. Chen and Wan (2019b) studied the violent sloshing under 1-DOF translational excitations by using a 3D GPU parallelized MPS model. This model was recently utilized to study the 3D effect of sloshing waves in cuboid tanks (Xie et al., 2020a). In (Wang et al., 2019a), the sloshing under 1-DOF rotational and translational excitations was simulated by an MPS model incorporating a background mesh scheme (producing a spatially more continuous PPE source term). Using MPS, Tsukamoto et al. (2020) studied the LNG sloshing of shallow to middle filling (5% - 20%) in a rectangular tank under 1-DOF rotational excitations. The effects of bottom and sidewall stiffeners (the corrugated stainless steel in a real membrane-type LNG tank) on the sloshing behavior were examined. It was found that, except for the 5% filling level, the sloshing response predicted based on a flat-wall tank excited by the corresponding resonant excitation could be adopted as a conservation estimation for the sloshing loads of the real tank with corrugated components.

Almost all the studies discussed above considered rectangular tanks. The membrane-type LNG tank that is taking increased market share is designed with chamfers to mitigate impact loads. Therefore, it is of practical importance to study sloshing waves in prismatic tanks. Besides, it is important to consider realistic excitations from ocean waves in order to produce guidance for practical designs. In this regard, Luo et al. (2016a) and Luo and Koh (2017) have studied the 3D sloshing under multi-DOF excitations by a novel CPM model (with mathematically consistent gradient and Laplacian operators) and well-controlled experiments. As shown in Fig. 6, violent swirling waves are generated by the rotational excitations. The complex sloshing patterns (top row) and the resulting violent impact pressures (middle row) have been captured accurately by CPM. These studies have provided important benchmark examples of sloshing under multi-DOF rotational excitations. Using the CPM, the LNG sloshing in a real LNG carrier under real sea conditions has also been studied. Results suggest that the sloshing waves in Beam Sea can cause more severe adverse effects than those in other sailing conditions. More recently, this case of violent sloshing flow has been reproduced by the δ-SPH method in You et al. (2021). As shown in the bottom row of Fig. 6, δ-SPH has produced promising results in terms of the free surface profile, and the pressure field has been further improved through the incorporation of the BM scheme in the δ-SPH + BM method. The capability of SPH in accurately reproducing challenging sloshing phenomena in complex 3D geometries has also been presented in a recent article by Green et al. (2021).

Some sloshing scenarios such as the flip-through entrap air pockets. The experimental study of Lugni et al. (2006) suggested that the entrapped air dynamics affect the local wave impact kinematics and dynamics significantly. It is very challenging to reproduce this process numerically due to the multi-physics and multi-scale nature (more discussions are provided in Section 3.4). In this direction, Colagrossi et al. (2010) simulated the flip-through sloshing by using a single-phase SPH model. Although the model satisfactorily predicted the peak of sloshing pressure, the authors pointed out that the pressure oscillations associated with the flip-through were not captured due to the ignorance of the air phase. Luo et al. (2016b) have designed a sloshing case in a ‘U’ shape container that involves a better-controlled, relatively-larger air pocket (easier to measure than the small-size ones). The violent sloshing waves and the resulting air pressure change in the air pocket have been successfully predicted by the CPM method that models the incompressible water and compressible air in a reliable and strongly-coupled way. Marrone et al. (2017) have studied the wet drop of flat and corrugated panels that mimic the wave slamming on LNG tank walls by using a Riemann-ALE SPH model. The simulation results affirm the necessity to include the air phase in predicting the wave impact pressures even at locations where air cushion is not evident. The wet drop of a corrugated panel has been simulated by a two-phase δ-SPH model in Hammani et al. (2020). In brief, more research efforts addressing the two-phase sloshing in real-shape LNG tanks would be valuable.

Due to the adverse effects of violent sloshing, sloshing-suppressing devices such as baffles have been invented to mitigate sloshing responses. In the particle method community, the fixed baffles have been studied extensively such as the vertical (Shao et al., 2012, Cao et al., 2014), horizontal and T-shape (Zheng et al., 2018b) baffles. Some studies have investigated the floating ones such as the constrained floating baffle (Koh et al., 2013) that is advantageous in minimizing the heat leak in membrane-type LNG tanks. In reality, the baffle is not infinitely rigid and hence the sloshing with deformable baffles has been simulated as introduced in Section 4.3. Some baffle systems have been shown to be effective in suppressing sloshing. The effectiveness, however, depends on the excitation frequency and/or amplitude and the filling ratio. Therefore, a baffle design that has been tested to be effective in a particular excitation and filling condition may not be effective for the other conditions, i.e., lack of versatility. In terms of this, it deserves more studies to explore self-adaptive baffle systems that can be applied to a broad range of excitations and filling conditions.

There are yet no documented particle-based simulations of liquid sloshing considering the phase change, to the best of authors’ knowledge. To address this, a physically thorough modelling of underlying thermodynamics and liquid-gas phase change would be required, in addition to a high-fidelity simulation of liquid and gaseous phases.

4.5.2. Marine renewable energy devices

The emerging marine renewable energy devices, due to their potential in reducing carbon emission, have been receiving increased interest, especially during the last decade. In the design and optimization of these devices, crucially important are the survivability analysis and the energy harvest efficiency analysis. These analyses have been handled numerically by particle methods owing to their inherent suitability for simulation of multi-phase/multi-physics WSI problems involving large deformations and violent flows. Stansby (2018) has presented an excellent, concise review that portrays the advances and future developments of both WCSPH and ISPH for offshore renewable energy applications.

For the oscillating water column (OWC), Crespo et al. (2017), by using DualSPHysics, conducted 3D single-phase simulations of the real-scale fixed and floating (constrained by catenary moorings) OWC devices under regular non-breaking waves. The model's capability in capturing free surface oscillations in the chambers was demonstrated. The 6-DOF motions and the mooring line forces of the floating device were discussed. The authors pointed out the necessity of including the air phase to model the pneumatic conversion of the OWC device. Wen et al. (2018b) presented a 2D single-phase SPH simulation of regular wave interaction with a fixed oscillating water chamber. The wave elevations inside the chamber and wave forces applied on the front wall of the device under different wave conditions were studied. The authors also recommended the modelling of the air phase in the chamber as future work. Zhu et al. (2020) studied the hydrodynamics of onshore OWC devices by using a single-phase SPH model with a pneumatic power-take-off (PTO) model (a regional ghost particle approach was proposed to model the thin wall of the OWC chamber).

For the oscillating wave surge converter (OWSC), Rafiee et al. (2013) simulated the flap type OWSC in regular waves by using a 3D SPH method with a RANS k-ε model for the turbulent flow. Huang et al. (2018) simulated the OWSC in regular waves by using a coupled finite particle method. Zhang et al. (2018) investigated the performance of a land hinged OWSC in regular waves by a 2D SPH model and found that the active power of the device depended on the PTO damping coefficient and the wave period. Marrone et al. (2019) conducted 2D and 3D SPH simulations of the extreme wave impacts on a wave surge convertor. The influences of the wave breaking inception, water depth and device movement on the impact loads exerted on the device were investigated. This study has shown that the loading process in some specific conditions behaved similarly to the ‘flip through’ impact on rigid walls, which induces intensive and localized pressures on the device. Liu et al. (2020b) investigated an OWSC consisting of a group of cylindrical sections and showed its merits over the rectangular one. The influences of five design parameters (load conditions, flap mass, hinge height from the seabed, damping of the PTO, and flap thickness) on the device's performance were examined. Brito et al. (2020) extended DualSPHysics to model the mechanical constraints (e.g., PTO, revolute joints, and frictional contacts) by coupling the multibody solver Project Chrono. Using the coupled model, the hydrodynamic properties of a rectangular OWSC, as well as their correlations with mechanical constraints, PTO damping coefficients and flap inertia, were investigated. Zhang et al. (2020b) simulated the flap type OWSC by using the open-source SPHinXsys and investigated the rotation of the flap and the wave loads exerted on the flap. Crespo et al. (2020) recently illustrated the capability of the DualSPHysics code in reproduction of interactions of slamming waves with a Wave Energy Converter (WEC), namely, a point-absorber comprising a cylindrical heaving-buoy with an air damper (reproducing the effect of the PTO system).

Other devices that have been studied based on particle methods include the asymmetric heaving floater, as in case of the study by Madhi and Yeung (2018), in which the authors investigated the impulsive forces applied by the jet-like flow impacts on the device in operational and survival modes. Pressure-relief channels that allow water to flow through the device were proposed, and their effectiveness in mitigating wave actions and enhancing the device's survivability was examined. The authors recommended future works on 3D simulations considering oblique incident waves. Canelas et al. (2018) incorporated the principle of Differential Variational Inequality into DualSPHysics for fluid-mechanism interaction and simulated the WaveStar wave energy converter and a passive tidal turbine. Based on a 2D SPH model, He et al. (2019) investigated the potential of a submerged horizontal plate as a wave energy breakwater. Wei et al. (2019) has presented a numerical model coupling GPUSPH and Project Chrono (Tasora et al., 2016) and utilized the model to simulate a conceptualized catenary mooring wave energy converter (CSI-Device) under different sea states. In the regular wave situation, the mooring line forces have been analyzed and it has been found that CSI-Device with a natural frequency close to the dominant wave period extracts more wave energy. The hydrodynamic properties of the device under directional spectrum waves have also been studied in the study by Wei et al. (2019). Ropero-Giralda et al. (2020) have portrayed the applicability of DualSPHysics code in simulation of a heaving point-absorber WEC with PTO, as well as conducted an efficiency analysis for different damping coefficients of the PTO and a survivability investigation through consideration of focused wave interactions with the WEC.

There has been an increase in global wave power as a consequence of oceanic warming (Reguero et al., 2019). Therefore, there is a need in the near future to consider more severe waves to fill the gap in that most of the existing studies have considered regular wave scenarios. Besides, the multi-physics modelling that would take into account, for instance, the structural dynamics of the energy device and the air compressibility in the chamber of OWC also needs to be further advanced.

5. Wave/current interaction with sediments

Marine mud or debris flows happen frequently when ambient excitations like earthquakes, storm waves and gas hydrates trigger submarine landslides, which may cause serious damages to infrastructures or generate tsunamis. In other circumstances when ocean waves/currents act on or pass through coastal (e.g., seawall, breakwater) and subsea (e.g., pipeline) structures, the change of fluid trajectory induces strong vortex shedding, which leads to the increase of local bed shear stress and stimulates undesirable sediment transport and scouring. Scouring is a serious issue for many marine and coastal structures. From the numerical point of view, scouring and the subsequent sediment transport are multi-phase phenomena involving water and soil phases that behave very differently, the former being a Newtonian fluid while the latter being a non-Newtonian fluid or granular flow. Due to the particle discretization feature, particle methods are advantageous in modelling the transport of sediments or deposit materials. However, it should be noted that most of documented particle-based simulations modeled the sediment material as a continuum, i.e., a numerical sediment particle representing a lump of real sediment grains. This is because the sediment grains can be very small and of irregular shape and hence it is impractical to model each individual grain. In the following, the particle-based simulations of wave-sediment interaction problems in ocean and coastal engineering will be reviewed in three categories, i.e. subaqueous mud/debris flow, scouring/erosion induced by wave/current, and sediment laden flow.

5.1. Subaqueous mud/debris flow

Early studies treating the subaerial mud or debris flow as a single-phase non-Newtonian flow (Shao and Lo, 2003, Laigle et al., 2007, Xenakis et al., 2015) paved the general strategy of modelling the non-Newtonian mudflow. The subaqueous mudflows involving the mud-water interaction can be modelled as a multi-density, multi-viscosity system and by using an appropriate rheological model to describe the non-Newtonian behaviour of the mud phase. In this regard, the Power-law (Vola et al., 2004), Bingham (Barnes et al., 1989) and Herschel-Bulkley (Tang and Kalyon, 2004) models have been adopted. In simulations, different types of particles need to be defined for the water phase, the moving soil and the fixed soil. The interaction between water and soil particles can be modelled by including all the neighboring particles in the influence domain irrespective of the particle type in the particle interpolation, which leads to a strong coupling. The weak coupling has also been adopted, in which the water and soil phases are solved sequentially, and their interactions are modelled explicitly.

Based on the strong coupling approach, Capone et al. (2010) simulated the submarine landslide (Rzadkiewicz et al., 1997) using a WCSPH model and investigated the resulting wave generation and propagation. The soil was simulated by a bi-viscosity Bingham model by specifying a threshold for the shear stress in soil with respect to the yield stress. Fu and Jin (2015) simulated the landslide rushing into water (Zweifel et al., 2007) based on a weakly-compressible MPS model. The landslide-induced wave profiles were satisfactorily predicted, while the sediment deformations showed discrepancies with the experimental data. The weakly-compressible MPS model was extended in Tajnesaie et al. (2018) by introducing a visco-plastic rheological model, i.e., μ(I), with a dynamic inter-grain mechanical pressure. The extended model was utilized to study the subaqueous landslide (Grilli et al., 2016). A comparison study showed that the μ(I) rheology model outperformed the Herschel-Bulkley slightly in terms of the granular profile. Hosseini et al. (2019) implemented the μ(I) model into SPHysics and studied the submarine landslide and sediment rushing into water. Krimi et al. (2018) proposed a multiphase diffusive term for mitigating spurious pressure fluctuations and simulated two benchmark cases of waves generated by submarine landslides. Recently, Jandaghian et al. (2021) presented a 3D weakly-compressible MPS model (equipped with a unified rheological model, a formulation for the effective pressure of solid skeletons, and a modified diffusive term) and studied a benchmark example of submarine landslide. Ghaïtanellis et al. (2021) portrayed the applicability of their advanced multi-phase SPH with a granular rheological model to simulate the 2007 Chehalis Lake landslide and the subsequent tsunami.

The strong coupling strategy of fluid-soil models has also been implemented in the projection-based particle methods. For example, Nabian and Farhadi (2017) presented an MPS model and studied the benchmark example of Rzadkiewicz et al. (1997). Xenakis et al. (2017) presented an ISPH model that incorporated turbulence of water and saturation of the sliding soil upon entering the water, which predicted the run-up height and landslide-entry profile of the Lituya Bay landslide satisfactorily well.

In the category of weak coupling, Shi et al. (2016) simulated the slow (Viroulet et al., 2013) and fast (Fritz et al., 2009) landslides rushing into the water using SPH. The morphological evolution of the sliding soil and generated waves were discussed. A feature of this solution framework was that the parameters in the rheological model could be determined from standard soil mechanics experiments. Based on a hybrid DEM-SPH model, Tan and Chen (2017) studied the submarine landslide. The effect of landslide rigidity on wave characteristics and the effect of particle friction coefficient on landslide motions were examined. Recently, large-scale 3D landslide-induced waves have been simulated by the coupled DEM-SPH model in Xu et al. (2020) and Xu and Dong (2021).

5.2. Scouring/erosion induced by wave/current

Another sediment-related problem in the ocean is the scouring/erosion of structural foundations or the coast caused by waves, currents, or a combination of the two. Different from subaqueous landslides where the sediment motion is normally dominated by gravity, the main driving forces of the sediment movements in scouring/erosion are the hydrodynamic force from wave/current and the accompanying turbulence effects. Specifically, a soil particle will start to move when it is subjected to resultant shear stress larger than the yield (or critical) shear stress.

Considerable research efforts have been dedicated in advancing the particle simulation technology for scouring/erosion since the early work of Shakibaeinia and Jin (2011). These works focused on different aspects such as the sediment yielding criteria (Manenti et al., 2012, Ran et al., 2015, Ghaïtanellis et al., 2018, Zubeldia et al., 2018), the rheological law (Pahar and Dhar, 2017a, Krimi et al., 2018), introducing more physics into the simulation (Fourtakas and Rogers, 2016, Zubeldia et al., 2018), the sediment-water mixture based simulation (Shi et al., 2019) and the coupled modelling (Tang et al., 2018). Although most of these studies were based on dambreak problems, the theoretical and numerical developments can be applied in particle-based simulation of oceanic/coastal scouring and erosion.

In the area of ocean and coastal engineering, Zanganeh et al. (2012) studied the current-induced scouring beneath marine pipelines by developing a two-phase SPH model that considered the fluid-sediment and sediment-sediment interactions. The bottom shear stress, scour gap and sediment transport rate during the erosion process were investigated. Ulrich et al. (2013) simulated the harbor bed erosion induced by the propeller of a full-scale ship and discussed the erosion pattern qualitatively. Nikeghbali and Omidvar (2017) studied the morphology changes of a movable bed under breaking and undular tidal bores. Wang et al. (2016a) studied the erosion induced by tsunami overflows by developing a multi-phase ISPH model. The logarithmic law of the boundary layer was employed to evaluate the tangential component of the shear stress for fixed (un-eroded) interface soil particles, and the Shields formula was adopted for calculating the critical shear stress. The 3D extension of the model was utilized to study the erosion caused by flows passing a vertical cylinder (Wang et al., 2018). Tsuruta et al. (2019) have proposed a comprehensive multi-phase and multi-physics SPH-based numerical wave flume, referred to as PARISPHERE, capable of reproducing wave interactions with solid bodies/soils including scouring, and have simulated the erosion induced by tsunami overflows. Liang et al. (2020) carried out two-point MPM simulations of the failure process of earth dikes subjected to overtopping flows. In this MPM study, water and soil were modelled by two sets of independently-moving material points, which could overlap to represent saturated soils.

The soil excavation by water jets has been the subject of some research works. Bui et al. (2007) simulated the erosion during excavation by water jets of velocities ranging from 1 m/s to 100 m/s. The erosion patterns for dry and saturated soils were qualitatively discussed and compared. Gotoh and Khayyer (2016) have presented an MPS simulation of scouring induced by vertical jet flows. An advection equation of sediment concentration has been solved to track the sediment movement. The predicted bed profiles have been in good agreement with documented experimental data. Yuan et al. (2019) have investigated the submerged soil excavation by plane wall jet and vertical impinging jet. The effects of the nozzle dimension and location, jet velocity, water flux, and soil cohesion on the crater pattern have been examined. This study has highlighted the role of soil dilatancy/compaction in affecting the solid volume fraction and pore fluid pressure during submerged soil excavation.

The coupled SPH-DEM simulations of coastal scouring have been reported recently. In this direction, Iwamoto et al. (2019) have studied the scouring failure of a composite caisson breakwater induced by a long-lasting (5 – 7 minutes) tsunami inundation and highlighted the leading role of scouring in causing the structural failure. Yeganeh-Bakhtiary et al. (2020) have studied the scouring induced by standing waves in front of the trunk section of a vertical breakwater. For the first time, the study has reported the recirculating sediment transport in front of the breakwater, which has been found to affect the formation of the scour hole and the maximum scour depth.

5.3. Sediment laden flow

This subsection concerns the sediment laden flows in the coastal and ocean environments. The first specific problem is the sand discharging into the water, which is related to coastal construction, dredging and reclamation. To reveal the mechanisms of this problem, Shakibaeinia and Jin (2012) developed a multiphase weakly-compressible MPS method (with the standard SPS turbulence model) and studied the cases of sand dumping and sand jet. In the sand dumping case, the jet flow, mixing process and settling of sand particles were satisfactorily predicted. In the sand jet case, the effects of flow conditions (i.e., nozzle diameter and particle Reynolds number) and rheological properties on the jet behavior were investigated. Shi et al. (2017) also studied the sand dumping by developing a sediment-water mixture based two-phase SPH model, in which the water and sediment phases were treated as miscible fluids governed by the conservation equations with volume fractions. Based on the model, the key physics of the sand dumping process were examined, including the front velocity and width of the sand cloud, the sediment concentration, the vortices induced by sediment setting, and the resulting free surface water motions. The sand dumping case was also simulated in Fonty et al. (2019) and Bertevas et al. (2019) by using sediment-water mixture SPH models.

The lock exchange phenomenon of suspended sediments has been studied in Ikari and Gotoh (2018) by developing a two-phase MPS model. The suspended sediment is described by a concentration defined on each particle with its transport being governed by an advection-diffusion equation. The propagation velocity of the density current and the deposit density variation of the suspended sediments have been investigated. This model has been extended in Ikari et al. (2020) by introducing an elastoplastic solid phase model for sediment particles on the seabed, on the basis of which, the authors have studied the diffusion of dumped sand from a split hopper. The spread of the suspended sediments, the deposition of sand, and the associated flow patterns have been elaborated via simultaneous consideration of numerical simulations and laboratory experiments.

Marine exploitation activities near the seabed can bring about turbulent sediment transport. This process has been studied by particle methods recently. By using a mixture SPH model, Tran-Duc et al. (2019) have simulated the 3D sediment dispersion induced by moving harvesting equipment in a local ocean area (4.5 km × 1.2 km × 50 m; around 3.4 million SPH particles) with an unidirectional current. The amount of re-suspended sediments, as well as their resettlement behavior under two equipment marching directions and two horizontal diffusivities, have been examined. Bertevas et al. (2019) have simulated the sediment/water mixture triggered by a partially buried moving plate. The pattern of sediment movements and the resulting vorticity and TKE have been analyzed with the support of experimental data.

Waves and currents cause sediment segregation in the swash/surf zone. Through applying an advanced coupled DEM-MPS multi-phase model, Harada et al. (2019) and Harada et al. (2020) have demonstrated the capability of particle methods in reproducing sediment transport and morphological changes in ocean and coastal engineering. Tazaki et al. (2021) have studied the vertical sorting process of a three-size mixed movable bed in an oscillating water tank by applying an MPS-DEM model and conducting laboratory experiments. The concentration centroid and horizontal velocity of sediment particles have been analyzed. Parametric studies based on the numerical model suggest that the pressure gradient force generates particle oscillations and then particle collisions, which further contribute to the vertical thrusting of sediments.

6. Concluding remarks and future perspectives

The paper presents a detailed review on the latest advances and developments in the field of Lagrangian meshfree, or particle methods, with applications in ocean and coastal engineering. The advances are categorized into advancements of numerical techniques, modeling of wave hydrodynamics, modeling of wave/current interaction with structures of different types and different material properties, and modeling of wave/current interaction with sediments. Significant enhancements have been made in the past decade to enhance the applicability and reliability of particle methods in applications to ocean and coastal engineering, especially for challenging problems that involve violent fluid motions and highly deformable moving boundaries.

Despite significant advances, several aspects require continued attention to further enhance the reliability and applicability of particle methods. These aspects include both the so-called Grand Challenges as specified by SPHERIC (Vacondio et al., 2021) and specific aspects related to precise reproduction of turbulence and accurate simulation of boundary layers. In this regard, particle methods need to be rigorously validated through systematic comparisons to proper reference solutions (including analytical and experimental data), and then to be compared to the state-of-the-art of technology corresponding to conventional grid-based methods. Followed by rigorous and systematic validations, the robustness of particle methods in specific fields and for specific applications need to be portrayed coherently. Table 2 summarizes several key developments corresponding to key challenges of particle methods along with some representative references. In addition to the five GCs (Grand Challenges) specified by SPHERIC, namely, i) Stability, Convergence & Consistency, ii) Boundary conditions, iii) Adaptivity, iv) Coupling to other models and v) Practical engineering/industrial applications, we have also included precise reproduction of turbulence as a distinct key challenge (although precise reproduction of turbulence would also be directly/indirectly linked with the resolution of other challenges including convergence, consistency and adaptivity).

In addition to the fundamental aspects of stability, accuracy, consistency (reproducibility), conservation and convergence, the particle method developers need to ensure consistency of their solution with respect to fundamental thermodynamic laws including the second law of thermodynamic, which is represented by Clausius-Duhem inequality in continuum mechanics. In this regard, the numerical method needs to be validated first by considering conservative systems in absence of physical dissipations to ensure that reversible thermodynamic conditions are well reproduced, and then the method can be applied to systems including irreversibility and physical dissipation.

The specific future research directions in ocean and coastal engineering can be classified into several research targets. Concerning wave hydrodynamics, precise reproduction of the turbulence field through systematic studies with rigorous verifications in terms of reproduced turbulence would be of crucial importance. Accurate resolution of the flow field and boundary layers near complex physical boundaries would be of vital importance as well. The detailed reproduction of air entrainment under broken waves and its interaction with ambient turbulent flows will be challenging to particle methods, but it provides a meaningful task to prove the possible advantage of particle methods in handling difficult multi-phase fluid problems. As for WSI, particle methods can be further upgraded to provide reliable estimations of structural damage/fracture. In this regard, extensions of WSI reproductions to include visco-elasto-plasticity would be of interest. In addition, more precise and realistic modelling of solid properties, e.g., consideration of anisotropy of material properties, would enhance the applicability/reliability of particle methods for practical engineering applications. As for wave interactions with permeable structures, rigorous considerations of deformable/compressible porous media skeleton would be of significance. As for wave/current interactions with sediments, developments of precise coupled particle methods, being capable of precisely handling the underlying physics, e.g., boundary layers and interfacial fluid-sediment stress fields, would be of prime importance.

In summary, the distinct advantageous features of particle methods have already made them strong candidates for a wide range of problems encountered in ocean and coastal engineering including violent turbulent flows, wave interactions with fixed/floating and rigid/deformable structures, sediment transport, and coastal morphological changes, etc. Meanwhile, to ensure precise and reliable reproductions, further validations, extensions, and comparative investigations must be conducted coherently and systematically with consideration of fundamental physics and establishment of a thorough mathematical-physical-numerical framework.
